INSERT INTO sat_questions (type, section, prompt, options, correct_answer, explanation, domain, difficulty_tier, module_number, set_number)
VALUES
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In certain high-energy astrophysical environments, atomic nuclei are stripped of their electrons, forming a plasma that behaves according to the principles of quantum electrodynamics. The phenomenon known as synchrotron radiation results when charged particles spiral through magnetic fields, emitting light across the electromagnetic ______ is frequently detected from pulsars and distant quasars. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"spectrum. It"},{"id":"B","text":"spectrum It"},{"id":"C","text":"spectrum, it"},{"id":"D","text":"spectrum and it"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation use between sentences. In this choice, the period after “spectrum” is used correctly to mark the boundary between one sentence (“In certain high-energy…electromagnetic spectrum”) and another (“It is frequently detected from pulsars and distant quasars”). The supplementary phrase (“emitting light across the electromagnetic spectrum”) modifies the main clause of the first sentence (“The phenomenon…fields”), and “It” is the subject of the second sentence. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence. The sentences (“In certain high-energy…spectrum” and “It is frequently detected…quasars”) are fused without punctuation and/or a conjunction. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a comma splice. A comma can’t be used in this way to mark the boundary between sentences. Choice D is incorrect. Without a comma preceding it, the conjunction “and” can’t be used in this way to join sentences.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While many climate modelers attempt to simulate fine-scale convective processes using nested high-resolution grids and parameterization schemes that demand enormous computational ______ others develop simplified stochastic approaches that capture aggregate behavior with far lower cost. (Such approaches sacrifice pointwise detail in order to represent system-level statistics.) Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"resources and"},{"id":"B","text":"resources"},{"id":"C","text":"resources,"},{"id":"D","text":"resources, and"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between a subordinate clause and a main clause. This choice correctly uses a comma to mark the boundary between the subordinate clause (“While many climate modelers attempt to simulate fine-scale convective processes using nested high-resolution grids and parameterization schemes that demand enormous computational resources”) and the main clause (“others develop simplified stochastic approaches that capture aggregate behavior with far lower cost”). Choice A is incorrect because it results in an incomplete sentence with no main clause following the conjunction. Choice B is incorrect because it fails to mark the boundary between the subordinate clause (“While many climate modelers…resources”) and the main clause (“others develop…cost”). Choice D is incorrect because it results in an incomplete sentence with no main clause following the conjunction.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The artist’s retrospective exhibition—held at the newly renovated Linden Gallery—features works spanning nearly five decades, during which she developed a distinctive visual language rooted in both surrealism and social realism; these paintings_______ The Dreamers—demonstrate, vividly, her ability to blend the two. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"—especially"},{"id":"B","text":": especially"},{"id":"C","text":", especially,"},{"id":"D","text":"especially"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of a supplementary element within a sentence. The dash before “especially” pairs with the dash after The Dreamers to separate the supplementary element “especially The Dreamers” from the rest of the sentence. Choice B is incorrect because a colon can’t be paired with a dash in this way to set off the supplementary element. Choice C is incorrect because commas can’t be paired with a dash in this way to separate the element. Choice D is incorrect because it fails to use appropriate punctuation to set off the supplementary element from the rest of the sentence.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Japanese filmmaker Hayao Miyazaki’s acclaimed body of work includes Spirited Away, an animated fantasy exploring the loss of innocence in a modernizing Japan_________ an ecological epic examining the clash between industrial progress and nature; and The Wind Rises, a historical drama reflecting on creativity and moral responsibility during wartime. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Japan, Princess Mononoke,"},{"id":"B","text":"Japan; Princess Mononoke,"},{"id":"C","text":"Japan, Princess Mononoke:"},{"id":"D","text":"Japan; Princess Mononoke"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of items in a complex series (a series including internal punctuation). In this choice, the semicolon after “Japan” is conventionally used to separate the first item (“Spirited Away, an animated fantasy…Japan”) and the second item (“Princess Mononoke, an ecological epic…nature”) in the series. Further, the comma after “Mononoke” correctly separates the title “Princess Mononoke” from the supplementary phrase (“an ecological epic…nature”) that describes it. Choice A is incorrect because the comma after “Japan” doesn’t match the semicolon used later in the series to separate the second item (“Princess Mononoke, an ecological epic…nature”) from the third item (“and The Wind Rises, a historical drama…”). Choice C is incorrect because the comma after “Japan” doesn’t match the later semicolon and because a colon can’t be used in this way to separate the title “Princess Mononoke” from the descriptive phrase that follows. Choice D is incorrect because it fails to use appropriate punctuation to separate the title “Princess Mononoke” from the descriptive phrase (“an ecological epic…nature”) that explains it.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The Warka Tower, designed by Italian architect Arturo Vittori, is a vertical structure that collects potable water from the atmosphere. Constructed primarily from bamboo and biodegradable materials, it functions entirely without external power, relying on ______ and condensation that forms on its mesh surface each morning. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"moisture gathered, by fine threads, during the night"},{"id":"B","text":"moisture, gathered by fine threads during the night,"},{"id":"C","text":"moisture gathered by fine threads during the night,"},{"id":"D","text":"moisture gathered by fine threads during the night"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is comma use with essential versus nonessential phrases. The phrase “gathered by fine threads during the night” is essential to the meaning of the noun moisture, specifying which moisture the tower relies on. Therefore, it should not be set off by commas. The sentence correctly reads: “...relying on moisture gathered by fine threads during the night.” Choice A is incorrect because the commas incorrectly separate “by fine threads” from the phrase it modifies, disrupting sentence flow. Choice B is incorrect because it sets off an essential phrase with commas, which would imply that the detail is merely additional, not defining. Choice C is incorrect because placing a comma at the end of the phrase before the main clause creates an unnecessary pause.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Biochemist Lila Fernández and her collaborators theorized that they could enhance the stability of the enzyme complex ZnCuSOD, a catalytic antioxidant composed of zinc (Zn), copper (Cu), and superoxide dismutase (SOD), by substituting zinc with manganese _______ the altered enzyme, MnCuSOD, proved markedly less effective at neutralizing reactive oxygen species. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"(Mn)"},{"id":"B","text":"(Mn) but"},{"id":"C","text":"(Mn),"},{"id":"D","text":"(Mn), but"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is punctuation between two independent clauses. This choice correctly uses a comma followed by the coordinating conjunction “but” to link two complete ideas: the first describing the researchers’ hypothesis (they could enhance stability by substituting zinc with manganese) and the second expressing the contrasting outcome (the altered enzyme proved less effective). The comma appropriately separates the clauses, and “but” accurately signals contrast. Choice A is incorrect because it joins two independent clauses without any punctuation or conjunction, creating a run-on sentence. Choice B is incorrect because it joins the clauses with a conjunction but omits the necessary comma. Choice C is incorrect because it uses only a comma between independent clauses, resulting in a comma splice. Choice D is correct because it both punctuates and coordinates the clauses properly while preserving the intended contrast between expectation and result.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Medical researchers estimate that more than half of all health articles attributed to doctors or nutrition experts are in fact written by science writers, professional journalists who are paid to present other _______ but whose names rarely appear in medical journals. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"specialists’ findings"},{"id":"B","text":"specialist’s findings"},{"id":"C","text":"specialists findings"},{"id":"D","text":"specialist’s finding"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of plural and possessive nouns. The plural possessive noun “specialists’” and the plural noun “findings” correctly indicate that the findings belong to multiple specialists. Choice B is incorrect because the singular possessive noun “specialist’s” suggests that the findings come from only one specialist, not several. Choice C is incorrect because it omits the possessive apostrophe, failing to show that the findings belong to the specialists. Choice D is incorrect because it uses the singular possessive form “specialist’s” and the singular noun “finding,” even though the context refers to multiple contributors and multiple findings.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A paper published by climate scientist Dr. Lila Fernandez in 2021 proposes a new model for understanding rapid ice sheet collapse in Antarctica, highlighting the role of feedback loops in accelerating melt and destabilizing the ice, which could dramatically influence global sea levels. The study emphasizes the need for updated predictive models to account for _______ phenomena called marine ice cliff instability, in which towering ice cliffs collapse into the ocean, triggering further retreat of the ice sheet. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"glacial physical"},{"id":"B","text":"glacial: physical"},{"id":"C","text":"glacial; physical"},{"id":"D","text":"glacial. Physical"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is the proper punctuation between adjectives and the nouns they modify within a noun phrase. In this sentence, “glacial” and “physical” both modify “phenomena,” forming a single noun phrase: “glacial physical phenomena.” No punctuation is needed between the adjectives and the noun, so choice A correctly presents the phrase without commas, semicolons, or colons. Choice B is incorrect because a colon is used to introduce a list, explanation, or amplification, not to separate adjectives from a noun. Choice C is incorrect because a semicolon cannot separate adjectives from the noun they modify; semicolons are only used to join independent clauses or separate complex items in a series. Choice D is incorrect because a period creates a sentence fragment; “Physical phenomena called marine ice cliff instability” would not form a complete sentence on its own.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Physical materials can be categorized by how well they conduct heat. Copper, which is classified as a good conductor, allows heat to pass _______ wood, which is classified as an insulator, allows very little heat to pass through. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"through quickly,"},{"id":"B","text":"through quickly"},{"id":"C","text":"through quickly;"},{"id":"D","text":"through quickly and"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer.The convention being tested is the coordination of main clauses within a sentence. This choice correctly uses a semicolon to join the first main clause (“Copper, which is classified as a good conductor, allows heat to pass through quickly”) with the second main clause (“wood, which is classified as an insulator, allows very little heat to pass through”). Choice A is incorrect because it creates a comma splice. Without a conjunction, a comma cannot properly join two independent clauses. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence. The two main clauses are fused without any punctuation or conjunction, which is grammatically incorrect. Choice D is incorrect because adding “and” suggests a single coordinated action rather than two separate, related clauses. For longer clauses like these, it is conventional to use a semicolon rather than a coordinating conjunction.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Using reclaimed ___________ discarded metal, such as soda cans; and more conventional building materials, such as cement, Indian architect Priya Sharma constructs her innovative eco-friendly furniture, which she hopes can inspire communities to rethink sustainable design practices. wood, such as old pallets; Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"wood, such as old pallets:"},{"id":"B","text":"wood, such as old pallets;"},{"id":"C","text":"wood, such as old pallets;"},{"id":"D","text":"wood; such as old pallets;"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is the punctuation of elements in a complex series. In a series where individual items contain internal punctuation (e.g., commas), it is conventional to use semicolons to separate the main items. In this sentence, the first item is “reclaimed wood, such as old pallets,” the second is “discarded metal, such as soda cans,” and the third is “more conventional building materials, such as cement.” Using a semicolon after the first item correctly separates it from the second item, which also contains a comma. Choice A is incorrect because a comma after “old pallets” does not match the semicolon used later to separate the second and third items in the series. Choice C is incorrect for the same reason: a comma fails to properly coordinate the complex series with internal punctuation. Choice D is incorrect because a semicolon inside the noun phrase (“wood; such as old pallets”) incorrectly separates the supplementary phrase from the noun it modifies.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Excavations at the ancient city of Çatalhöyük have revealed murals depicting complex hunting scenes, suggesting that early societies had organized communal activities earlier than had been _______ observation that, if verified, would challenge previous assumptions about Neolithic social structures. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"assumed; an"},{"id":"B","text":"assumed. An"},{"id":"C","text":"assumed an"},{"id":"D","text":"assumed, an"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is the use of punctuation to separate a main clause from a supplementary element. Choice D correctly uses a comma to mark the boundary between the main clause (“...had been assumed”) and the supplementary element (“an observation that, if verified, would challenge previous assumptions...”), which provides additional information about the implications of the discovery. Choice A is incorrect because a semicolon cannot appropriately join a main clause and a supplementary phrase like this. Choice B is incorrect because a period creates a sentence fragment beginning with “An observation,” which is grammatically incomplete. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a run-on sentence, fusing the main clause and the supplementary element without any punctuation.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'While composing A Brief History of Time (1988), physicist Stephen Hawking aimed to explain complex cosmological ideas to a general audience. The book became a global bestseller, but Hawking’s research _______ recognized long before its publication. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"were"},{"id":"B","text":"have been"},{"id":"C","text":"has been"},{"id":"D","text":"are"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject–verb agreement. The singular verb “has been” correctly agrees in number with the singular subject “research.” Choice A is incorrect because the plural verb “were” doesn’t agree in number with the singular subject research. Choice B is incorrect because the plural verb “have been” doesn’t agree with research. Choice D is incorrect because the plural verb “are” also fails to agree with the singular subject research.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1975, Junko Tabei became the first woman to reach the summit of Mount Everest. Her meticulous preparation before each climb and her calm determination in extreme _______ transform the traditionally male-dominated image of mountaineering into one of inclusivity and perseverance. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"weather helped"},{"id":"B","text":"weather, helping"},{"id":"C","text":"weather that helped"},{"id":"D","text":"weather to help"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is finite verb use in a main clause. A main clause requires a finite verb to show what the subject (here, Tabei’s “preparation” and “determination”) did, and this choice provides the finite past tense verb “helped,” correctly completing the sentence. Choice B is incorrect because the participle “helping” creates a fragment—it does not supply the sentence with a main verb. Choice C is incorrect because the relative clause “that helped” introduces unnecessary subordination and still leaves the main clause without a finite verb. Choice D is incorrect because the infinitive “to help” does not function as a finite verb and fails to complete the clause grammatically.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1953, Mexican architect Luis Barragán captured the interplay of light and color in two iconic designs: Casa Estudio and Torres de Satélite. In 2018, _________ featured alongside dozens of Barragán’s other creations in a major retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art in New York. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"it was"},{"id":"B","text":"they were"},{"id":"C","text":"this was"},{"id":"D","text":"some were"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The convention being tested is pronoun–antecedent agreement. The plural pronoun “they” agrees in number with the plural antecedent “Casa Estudio and Torres de Satélite” and clearly identifies what was featured in the retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art. Choice A is incorrect because the singular pronoun “it” doesn’t agree in number with the plural antecedent. Choice C is incorrect because the singular pronoun “this” doesn’t agree in number with the plural antecedent. Choice D is incorrect because the plural pronoun “some” is illogical in this context, as it implies more than two works were selected, whereas the sentence specifically refers to the two iconic designs.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The score for Ang Lee’s 2005 film Brokeback Mountain vividly conveys the emotional tension that unfolds between ________ (Ennis Del Mar and Jack Twist, two cowboys in rural Wyoming). Featured throughout the film are compositions by Gustavo Santaolalla, traditional country and folk songs, and the original piano pieces performed by the film’s ensemble. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. it’s two protagonists"},{"id":"B","text":"B. its two protagonist’s"},{"id":"C","text":"C. it’s two protagonist’s"},{"id":"D","text":"D. its two protagonists"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The conventions being tested are the use of possessive determiners and plural nouns. The singular possessive determiner “its”—which agrees in number with the singular noun phrase “Ang Lee’s 2005 film Brokeback Mountain”—and the plural noun “protagonists” correctly indicate that the film has multiple protagonists. Choice A is incorrect because “it’s” is a contraction for “it is,” not a possessive determiner. Choice B is incorrect because the context requires the plural noun “protagonists,” not the singular possessive noun “protagonist’s.” Choice C is incorrect because the context requires the possessive determiner “its” and the plural noun “protagonists,” not the contraction “it’s” or the singular possessive noun “protagonist’s.”', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Public-health initiatives promoting vaccination can be effective, notes epidemiologist Ravi Patel of the University of Delhi, when these initiatives directly engage communities: for example, South Korea increased flu-vaccine uptake by 35 percent after healthcare workers asked residents whether _______ wished to receive the vaccine. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"they"},{"id":"B","text":"one"},{"id":"C","text":"you"},{"id":"D","text":"it"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The convention being tested is pronoun-antecedent agreement. The plural pronoun “they” agrees in number with the plural antecedent “residents.” Choice B is incorrect because the singular pronoun “one” does not agree in number with the plural antecedent “residents.” Choice C is incorrect because the second-person pronoun “you” is not conventional as a substitute for “residents,” as it implies addressing the audience rather than the subject of the sentence. Choice D is incorrect because the singular pronoun “it” does not agree in number with the plural antecedent “residents.”', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Seeking to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 11 Moon landing, ____________ a slogan that best encapsulated the spirit of space exploration. The council chose “One Giant Leap for Mankind,” submitted by Houston-based science writer Laura Chen, as the winning entry. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. a competition organized by the National Space Council would offer $500 to an individual who could devise"},{"id":"B","text":"B. an award of $500 would be given to an individual in a competition organized by the National Space Council for devising"},{"id":"C","text":"C. $500 would be awarded to an individual by the National Space Council in a competition for devising"},{"id":"D","text":"D. the National Space Council organized a competition offering $500 to an individual who could devise"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. The convention being tested is subject-modifier placement. This choice makes the noun phrase “the National Space Council” the subject of the sentence and places it immediately after the modifying phrase “seeking to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 11 Moon landing.” In doing so, this choice clearly establishes that the National Space Council—and not another noun in the sentence—sought to commemorate the anniversary. Choice A is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “a competition” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the competition itself wanted to commemorate the anniversary. Choice B is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “an award of $500” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the award wanted to commemorate the anniversary. Choice C is incorrect because it results in a dangling modifier. The placement of the noun phrase “$500” immediately after the modifying phrase illogically suggests that the money wanted to commemorate the anniversary.', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The human brain is highly attuned to patterns—so much so that, because of a cognitive bias known as apophenia, _______ will detect meaningful connections in random events, stock market fluctuations, and sequences of numbers. Psychologist Richard Wiseman has devoted his research to exploring this ubiquitous tendency. Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. she"},{"id":"B","text":"B. they"},{"id":"C","text":"C. it"},{"id":"D","text":"D. those"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. "It" is a singular pronoun that correctly refers to the singular antecedent "the human brain," making the sentence grammatically correct. Choice A is incorrect because "she" is reserved for people or animals, not inanimate objects like "the human brain." Choice B is incorrect because "they" is plural, whereas the antecedent is singular. Choice D is incorrect because "those" is also plural and does not agree with the singular antecedent "the human brain."', 'standard-english', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Astronomers have long considered Jupiter to be the largest planet in our solar system, with a diameter of about 142,984 kilometers. ___________ recent observations from the James Webb Space Telescope indicate that the exoplanet HD 100546 b may be even larger, with an estimated diameter exceeding 150,000 kilometers. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Secondly,"},{"id":"B","text":"Consequently,"},{"id":"C","text":"Moreover,"},{"id":"D","text":"However,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “However” logically signals that this sentence, which indicates that the exoplanet HD 100546 b may be larger than Jupiter, offers a contrast to or refutation of the previous assumption that Jupiter is the largest planet in our solar system. Choice A is incorrect because “secondly” illogically signals that this sentence merely offers an additional or secondary point concerning the previous assumption that Jupiter is the largest planet. Instead, the sentence offers a contrast to or refutation of that assumption. Choice B is incorrect because “consequently” illogically signals that this sentence offers a result or consequence of the previous assumption that Jupiter is the largest planet. Instead, the sentence offers a contrast to or refutation of that assumption. Choice C is incorrect because “moreover” illogically signals that this sentence merely adds to the previous assumption that Jupiter is the largest planet. Instead, the sentence offers a contrast to or refutation of that assumption.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'When a lightning bolt strikes, it rapidly heats the surrounding air to temperatures higher than the surface of the Sun. This extreme heating causes the air to expand explosively, _______ producing the powerful sound waves we recognize as thunder. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"moreover,"},{"id":"B","text":"in turn,"},{"id":"C","text":"otherwise,"},{"id":"D","text":"on the contrary,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “In turn” logically signals that the information in the sentence—that the rapid heating of air produces thunder—is a result or consequence of the previous information about lightning heating the air to extreme temperatures. Choice A is incorrect because “moreover” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is an additional or similar fact about lightning heating the air. Instead, the new information describes a direct consequence of that heating. Choice C is incorrect because “otherwise” illogically signals that the information in this sentence would occur only if the previous event did not happen. Instead, thunder occurs because of the rapid heating of the air, not in its absence. Choice D is incorrect because “on the contrary” illogically signals that the information in the sentence contrasts with the previous information about lightning heating the air. Instead, it presents a direct result of that process.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Historian Robert Caro observes that President Lyndon B. Johnson “thrived on the mechanics of power,” constantly refining his political strategies even after achieving major victories. However, the contrasts between his early Senate campaigns and his later presidential maneuvers are striking, even by Johnson’s standards; __________ some analysts regard them as two distinct phases of his political identity altogether. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"by contrast,"},{"id":"B","text":"in fact,"},{"id":"C","text":"nevertheless,"},{"id":"D","text":"in other words,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “In fact” logically signals that the analysts’ claim at the end of this sentence—that Johnson’s early and later political styles represent two distinct phases of his political identity—offers additional emphasis in support of the previous claim that the contrasts between his Senate campaigns and presidential maneuvers are striking. Choice A is incorrect because “by contrast” illogically signals that the claim at the end of this sentence contrasts with the previous claim about the differences between Johnson’s early and later political styles. Instead, the analysts’ opinion reinforces that claim by emphasizing how substantial those differences are. Choice C is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals that the claim at the end of this sentence is true despite the previous claim about the contrasts between Johnson’s early and later political behavior. Instead, the analysts’ opinion supports that claim. Choice D is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that the claim at the end of this sentence merely restates or paraphrases the previous claim about Johnson’s political differences. The analysts’ view instead adds new information, emphasizing the extent of those differences.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Neurons are specialized cells that are part of the nervous system. These cells transmit signals between different parts of the body. ____________ they help coordinate vital functions such as movement, sensation, and thought. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Additionally,"},{"id":"B","text":"Previously,"},{"id":"C","text":"In conclusion,"},{"id":"D","text":"Instead,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Additionally” logically signals that neurons’ role in coordinating vital functions such as movement, sensation, and thought is an additional function of these specialized nervous system cells that is separate from their role in transmitting signals between different parts of the body. Choice B is incorrect because “previously” illogically signals that the activity described in this sentence occurs earlier in a chronological sequence of events than the signal transmission described in the previous sentence. Instead, coordinating vital functions is an additional role of neurons that is separate from their role in transmitting signals. Choice C is incorrect because “in conclusion” illogically signals that the description of neurons’ role in coordinating vital functions summarizes the previous information about neurons. Instead, coordinating vital functions is one of the two distinct roles of neurons described in the text. Choice D is incorrect because “instead” illogically signals that the activity described in this sentence happens in place of the activity of transmitting signals described in the previous sentence. Rather, coordinating vital functions is an additional role of neurons.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2022, marine biologists observed an unexpected rise in harmful algal blooms along the Pacific coastline. These blooms were rapidly depleting oxygen levels in shallow waters, endangering several fish species. _______ regional conservation authorities temporarily restricted fishing activities while researchers investigated long-term mitigation strategies. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"B","text":"As a result,"},{"id":"C","text":"For instance,"},{"id":"D","text":"In contrast,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “As a result” logically signals that the action described in this sentence—regional conservation authorities temporarily restricting fishing activities—occurred as a consequence of the harmful algal blooms rapidly depleting oxygen levels and endangering fish species. Choice A is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that the action of restricting fishing activities is similar to the rise in algal blooms or the oxygen depletion described in the previous sentence. Instead, the fishing restrictions occurred as a result of those conditions. Choice C is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that restricting fishing activities serves as an example of the algal blooms or their effects. Instead, the restrictions occurred as a response to the threat posed by the blooms. Choice D is incorrect because “in contrast” illogically signals that the action of restricting fishing activities is being compared to the harmful algal blooms or their impact. Instead, the fishing restrictions occurred as a consequence of the ecological danger described in the previous sentence.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'When, in 2015, engineering students Priya Shah and Daniel Kim set out to design a community-focused technology project, one of their priorities was to create a device that could make everyday tasks easier for older adults. _______ they developed an adaptive smart home sensor system that alerts caregivers when residents may need assistance. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"In other words,"},{"id":"B","text":"In summary,"},{"id":"C","text":"For example,"},{"id":"D","text":"To that end,"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer. “To that end” logically signals that the information in this sentence—the students’ development of an adaptive smart home sensor system—is the product of a goal or desire in the previous sentence (the students’ priority of designing technology that supports older adults). Choice A is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is a paraphrase or restatement of the previous information about the students’ priority of designing supportive technology. Instead, the smart home system is the result of that goal. Choice B is incorrect because “in summary” illogically signals that the information in this sentence summarizes the previous information about the students’ intentions. Instead, the smart home system is the product of those intentions, not a summary of them. Choice C is incorrect because “for example” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is merely an example of the students’ stated priority. Instead, the smart home system is the direct outcome of that priority.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1928, the young chemist June Ellery secured a coveted research post at a renowned Berlin laboratory. She was collaborating closely with leading European physicists and gaining access to cutting-edge experimental equipment that most researchers could only dream of. _______ Ellery felt increasingly drawn to return to her small coastal hometown, convinced that the quiet environment there would allow her to pursue her ideas more freely. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Still,"},{"id":"B","text":"Consequently,"},{"id":"C","text":"Moreover,"},{"id":"D","text":"In fact,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Still” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that Ellery wanted to leave Berlin and return to her hometown—contrasts with what one would expect after reading about the exceptional opportunities she enjoyed at a prestigious research laboratory. Choice B is incorrect because “consequently” illogically signals that Ellery’s desire to leave Berlin is a result or consequence of her excellent research conditions. Instead, this desire contrasts with what those conditions would lead one to expect. Choice C is incorrect because “moreover” illogically signals that the information in this sentence adds support to the idea that Ellery was thriving in Berlin. Instead, her wish to return home contradicts expectations set by the previous sentences. Choice D is incorrect because “in fact” illogically signals that the information in this sentence reinforces or confirms the previous descriptions of her promising research situation. Instead, Ellery’s desire to leave Berlin runs counter to what those descriptions imply.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1996, astronomer Vera Rubin published a series of observations that strengthened scientific understanding of dark matter. Her work greatly shaped how researchers modeled the structure and behavior of galaxies. _______ it provided the crucial evidence needed to refine several leading theories about galactic rotation. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Nevertheless,"},{"id":"B","text":"Specifically,"},{"id":"C","text":"On the contrary,"},{"id":"D","text":"Previously,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Specifically” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that Rubin’s work provided crucial evidence used to refine theories of galactic rotation—offers precise, concrete details elaborating on the previous sentence’s more general claim about her influence on galaxy research. Choice A is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is true despite the earlier claim about Rubin’s work shaping galaxy models. Instead, the sentence supports and elaborates on that claim. Choice C is incorrect because “on the contrary” illogically signals that the information in this sentence contradicts the previous claim about her influence. Instead, it provides a detailed example that reinforces that influence. Choice D is incorrect because “previously” illogically signals that the information in this sentence refers to something that occurred before the influence described in the previous sentence. Instead, the sentence offers specific details expanding on the claim about the impact of Rubin’s 1996 observations.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Carved into the cliffs of Jordan’s ancient city of Petra are monumental façades whose full scale becomes clear only when viewed from a distance. Historians have known of these structures since early explorers documented them in the nineteenth century, and researchers have continued to investigate their origins ever since. ________ these studies are enhanced by 3D-mapping tools that generate detailed digital reconstructions of the site. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Today,"},{"id":"B","text":"In comparison,"},{"id":"C","text":"Still,"},{"id":"D","text":"However,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Today” logically signals that the studies using 3D-mapping tools (a present-day technology) are the current continuation of the ongoing research described in the previous sentence about historians and researchers investigating Petra’s structures. Choice B is incorrect because “in comparison” illogically signals that the use of 3D-mapping tools offers a comparison to the ongoing research, rather than indicating a present-day continuation of it. Choice C is incorrect because “still” illogically suggests that the action occurs despite the ongoing research. Instead, the use of 3D-mapping tools is a continuation and enhancement of that research. Choice D is incorrect because “however” illogically signals contrast or opposition to the ongoing research described previously. In fact, 3D-mapping tools support and extend the ongoing studies rather than contradicting them.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Some members of the National Endowment for the Arts have opposed allocating substantial grants to experimental performance art, arguing that certain works prioritize shock value over aesthetic rigor. _______ these administrators caution that many audiences might misinterpret abstract pieces, reducing public appreciation of serious artistic endeavors. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"However,"},{"id":"B","text":"Additionally,"},{"id":"C","text":"In contrast,"},{"id":"D","text":"For instance,"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. “Additionally” logically signals that the claim in this sentence—that administrators worry audiences may misinterpret abstract pieces—adds to the information in the previous sentence. Specifically, the first sentence presents one concern about experimental performance art (prioritizing shock value over rigor), and the second sentence provides a second, supplementary concern about public reception. Choice A is incorrect because “however” illogically signals contrast. In reality, the second concern complements the first rather than opposing it. Choice C is incorrect because “in contrast” illogically suggests a comparison that contradicts the first concern. Instead, the two concerns are cumulative. Choice D is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that the sentence provides an example of the previous claim. Instead, it introduces a distinct, additional concern.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'During the late 19th century, temperance advocates in Boston promoted the cause of alcohol prohibition by distributing pamphlets detailing the dangers of excessive drinking. Local chapters handed out guides at community gatherings and public lectures. _______ in Chicago, activist Mary Whitman circulated illustrated leaflets at neighborhood libraries and churches. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"For instance,"},{"id":"B","text":"To conclude,"},{"id":"C","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"D","text":"In other words,"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer. “Similarly” logically signals that the activity described in this sentence—Mary Whitman distributing leaflets in Chicago—is like the activity described in the previous sentence (Boston chapters handing out pamphlets at public gatherings). Together, these examples support the preceding claim that temperance advocates promoted prohibition by distributing educational materials. Choice A is incorrect because “for instance” illogically signals that the activity in Chicago is merely an example of the Boston activity. In reality, the Chicago activity is a parallel effort, not an isolated example. Choice B is incorrect because “to conclude” illogically signals that the Chicago activity summarizes or ends the discussion of Boston efforts. Instead, it is a parallel, similar action. Choice D is incorrect because “in other words” illogically signals that the Chicago activity paraphrases the Boston activity. Instead, both actions are similar but distinct efforts that collectively support the broader claim about temperance advocacy.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Volcanic lightning—streaks of electricity observed during eruptions—is a spectacular phenomenon that results from interactions within volcanic plumes. _______ friction between ash particles generates static charges that build up, eventually discharging as lightning. Scientists continue to study how the density and composition of volcanic ash influence the intensity of these electrical storms. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Specifically,"},{"id":"B","text":"Similarly,"},{"id":"C","text":"Nevertheless,"},{"id":"D","text":"Consequently,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “Specifically” logically signals that the information in this sentence—friction between ash particles generating static charges and producing lightning—provides precise details about the general phenomenon described in the previous sentence (that volcanic lightning results from interactions within volcanic plumes). Choice B is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that this sentence describes something comparable to the general information about volcanic lightning. Instead, it provides specific mechanistic details. Choice C is incorrect because “nevertheless” illogically signals contrast or contradiction with the previous sentence. Instead, the sentence elaborates on the same phenomenon. Choice D is incorrect because “consequently” illogically signals a result of the previous statement, as if volcanic lightning occurs because of the general phenomenon, rather than providing a mechanistic explanation.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Most species of oaks (genus Quercus) are deciduous, shedding their leaves each autumn. That is, they enter a period of dormancy during winter. However, some oak species are evergreen. Holm oaks, _______ retain their leaves throughout the year. Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', '[{"id":"A","text":"for example,"},{"id":"B","text":"nonetheless,"},{"id":"C","text":"similarly,"},{"id":"D","text":"additionally,"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. “For example” logically signals that the information in this sentence—that holm oaks retain their leaves year-round—is an example illustrating the claim in the previous sentence (that some oak species are evergreen). Choice B is incorrect because “nonetheless” illogically signals that the information in this sentence occurs in spite of the claim about oak species in the previous sentence. Instead, it is an example supporting that claim. Choice C is incorrect because “similarly” illogically signals that the information in this sentence is similar to the previous claim about oak species shedding leaves. Instead, it exemplifies the contrasting evergreen species. Choice D is incorrect because “additionally” illogically signals that the information in this sentence merely adds to the previous statement. Instead, it provides a specific example supporting the claim about evergreen oaks.', 'expression-of-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1997, a research team led by climate scientist Lonnie Thompson drilled three deep ice cores from the Dasuopu Glacier in the Himalayas. Despite extremely harsh conditions and limited logistical support, the team successfully _______ these cores, which later provided scientists with detailed records of precipitation, monsoon strength, and air pollution spanning several centuries. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"attached"},{"id":"B","text":"extracted"},{"id":"C","text":"followed"},{"id":"D","text":"replaced"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of a climate research team obtaining ice cores from the Dasuopu Glacier. In this context, “extracted” means removed or pulled out for use or study. The text indicates that although the team faced harsh conditions and limited logistical support, they successfully obtained deep ice cores that later allowed scientists to analyze centuries of environmental data. This context suggests that the team successfully extracted the ice cores. Choice A is incorrect because in this context “attached” means connected or affixed. The text explains that the team drilled and obtained deep ice cores; it does not suggest that they attached anything to the glacier. Choice C is incorrect because in this context “followed” means tracked or traveled behind. The text discusses how the team removed ice cores for scientific study, not that they tracked or traveled behind anything taken from the glacier. It is unclear what it would mean for researchers to “follow” the cores. Choice D is incorrect because in this context “replaced” means put back or returned. The text indicates that the team obtained ice cores so they could be studied; it does not suggest that they returned anything to the glacier.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Recent research by paleoclimatologist Dr. Elaine Kovács indicates that tree rings from certain ancient conifer forests may not reliably _______ abrupt shifts in prehistoric temperature. Because these trees grew in unusually stable microclimates, periods of sudden cooling or warming might not have produced noticeable growth changes; therefore, crucial evidence of rapid climate events could be missing from their ring patterns. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"transport"},{"id":"B","text":"reflect"},{"id":"C","text":"divide"},{"id":"D","text":"measure"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the limitations of using tree rings to study abrupt prehistoric temperature changes. In this context, “reflect” means represent or show accurately. The text explains that because these trees grew under stable conditions, their rings might not show the expected variations that correspond to sudden climate shifts. This context suggests that the tree rings may not reliably reflect those changes. Choice A is incorrect because “transport” means carry or move from one place to another. The text discusses whether tree rings can represent climate changes, not whether they can move or convey physical objects. Choice C is incorrect because “divide” means separate into parts. The sentence does not suggest that the function of tree rings is to separate or categorize climate events, only to indicate them. Choice D is incorrect because “measure” means calculate or quantify. While tree rings can measure growth, the focus of the sentence is not on quantifying size but on whether the rings accurately represent abrupt temperature changes.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The global market for residential solar panels reached record sales in 2022, with homeowners installing rooftop systems at unprecedented rates. Anticipating increasing demand as panel efficiency improves, industry experts _______ that annual installations will surge even further over the next decade. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"insisted"},{"id":"B","text":"predicted"},{"id":"C","text":"apologized"},{"id":"D","text":"prevented"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the growing residential solar panel market. As used in this context, “predicted” means forecast or stated that something would likely happen in the future. The text indicates that sales reached record highs in 2022 and that demand is expected to continue increasing, which suggests that experts predicted a further surge in installations. Choice A is incorrect because it wouldn’t make sense in context to say that industry experts “insisted,” or demanded forcefully, that installations will surge; the sentence focuses on projecting future growth, not forcefully stating an opinion. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not suggest that experts “apologized,” or expressed regret, about rising solar panel demand. Nothing in the passage implies that regret or wrongdoing is involved. Choice D is incorrect because “prevented” means stopped something from happening. The text indicates that experts expect installations to continue rising, not that they stopped or attempted to stop future increases.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Wildlife biologists often face challenges when studying bat behavior because many species forage in dense forest canopies that are hard to observe visually. Traditional monitoring methods like mist-netting can disrupt their natural flight paths. However, recent studies combining LiDAR-based 3D vegetation mapping with microphone-array acoustic tracking have enabled researchers to _______ this problem by precisely locating bat flight paths in relation to vegetation structure. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"exaggerate"},{"id":"B","text":"ignore"},{"id":"C","text":"circumvent"},{"id":"D","text":"validate"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of addressing an obstacle in studying bat behavior. In this context, “circumvent” means to find a way around or successfully avoid a difficulty. The text indicates that monitoring bats in dense forest canopies is challenging and that traditional methods may disrupt natural flight patterns. However, recent research shows that combining LiDAR-based 3D vegetation mapping with microphone-array acoustic tracking allows scientists to work around that challenge by locating bat flight paths without interfering with them. This context suggests that these technologies enable researchers to circumvent the problem of visually inaccessible bat foraging behavior. Choice A is incorrect because it would not make sense in context to say that researchers have shown it may be possible to “exaggerate,” or overstate, the challenge of monitoring bats. The difficulty of observing bat activity is presented in the text as an established fact, not something researchers would want to overstate. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not suggest that researchers are able to “ignore,” or disregard, the problem. Instead, it indicates that they have identified a method for dealing productively with the difficulty. Choice D is incorrect because it would not make sense to say that researchers have shown it may be possible to “validate,” or confirm, the problem by using these technologies. According to the text, LiDAR and acoustic tracking help scientists overcome the challenge, not merely confirm that such a challenge exists.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'he James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) has allowed astronomers to analyze the atmospheres of distant exoplanets with unprecedented precision. In 2023, for example, JWST observations detected carbon dioxide and possible dimethyl sulfide in the atmosphere of the exoplanet K2-18 b, offering new clues about its potential habitability. Scientists note that JWST’s powerful infrared instruments enable them to _______ molecules that were previously impossible to identify at such distances. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"disregard"},{"id":"B","text":"detect"},{"id":"C","text":"imitate"},{"id":"D","text":"replace"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s explanation of what JWST enables astronomers to do. In this context, “detect” means to discover or identify, which matches the statement that JWST observations revealed carbon dioxide and potential dimethyl sulfide in the atmosphere of K2-18 b. The text clearly describes scientists identifying atmospheric molecules, so the idea that JWST allows them to detect such molecules is consistent with the context. Choice A is incorrect because “disregard” means to ignore, which contradicts the purpose of examining exoplanet atmospheres. The text shows that scientists pay close attention to these molecules, not ignore them. Choice C is incorrect because “imitate” means to copy or mimic, which makes no sense in the context of analyzing atmospheric chemistry. Scientists are not copying the molecules; they are identifying them. Choice D is incorrect because “replace” means to take the place of something else. Nothing in the text suggests that JWST replaces atmospheric molecules; it simply detects them at great distances.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In addition to being an accomplished psychologist himself, Francis Cecil Sumner was a _______ increasing the opportunity for Black students to study psychology, helping to found the psychology department at Howard University, a historically Black university, in 1930. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"critic of"},{"id":"B","text":"novice in"},{"id":"C","text":"proponent of"},{"id":"D","text":"substitute for"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Francis Cecil Sumner. As used in this context, “proponent of” means supporter or advocate of. The text states that Sumner helped to found the psychology department at Howard University in 1930 in order to expand opportunities for Black students to study psychology. This clearly indicates that Sumner supported increasing such opportunities, so describing him as a proponent of this goal best fits the sentence. Choice A is incorrect because a critic of increasing opportunity would be someone who opposed or argued against it, which contradicts the text’s description of Sumner actively helping to create a psychology department for Black students. Choice B is incorrect because a novice in something is a beginner. The text identifies Sumner as an accomplished psychologist, which directly conflicts with the idea that he was a beginner in increasing opportunities for Black psychology students. Choice D is incorrect because a substitute for would mean a replacement for something else, which does not make sense in context. Sumner was not replacing another person or initiative; rather, he was advocating for and expanding educational access.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from the 1903 novel The Call of the Wild by Jack London. Buck, a powerful dog stolen from a ranch in California, has been sold into work as a sled dog in the Yukon. The trail was faint, the cold was bitter, and every hour demanded a struggle for mere existence. Yet Buck adjusted quickly to the brutal conditions. He learned not to leave the slightest sign of meat when he ate, for other dogs would seize upon any scrap that suggested a meal. The law of club and fang left no room for waste, and no mark of weakness could be afforded. As used in the text, what does the word “sign” most nearly mean?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Gesture"},{"id":"B","text":"Indication"},{"id":"C","text":"Symbol"},{"id":"D","text":"Prediction"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because the passage emphasizes Buck’s need to avoid leaving any evidence of food that other dogs might take. The text clarifies that he learned not to leave “the slightest sign” of meat, meaning no indication that food had been present. This matches the meaning of indication. Choice A is incorrect because while “sign” can mean a gesture, the text does not describe Buck making motions or signals; it focuses on the remains of food that might attract other dogs. Choice C is incorrect because a symbol refers to something representing an idea, and nothing in the context suggests that the trace of meat would carry symbolic meaning. Choice D is incorrect because a prediction is a statement about the future, and the passage instead concerns physical evidence that could lead other dogs to food, not a forecast.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Whether the reforms of an Inca emperor such as Pachacuti or Huayna Capac were transformative or largely administrative, their success depended on networks of reciprocity and religious authority and therefore cannot be examined without a corollary understanding of the strategies that enabled the ruler to _______ his claim to imperial power. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"replicate"},{"id":"B","text":"illuminate"},{"id":"C","text":"buttress"},{"id":"D","text":"rescind"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the legitimacy and authority of Inca emperors such as Pachacuti and Huayna Capac. As used in this context, “buttress” means to strengthen or support. The sentence explains that whether the emperor’s reforms were impactful or minor, their success depended on religious and political structures that reinforced imperial authority. This context suggests that the ruler would need strategies to buttress, or support and defend, his claim to power. Choice A is incorrect because “replicate” means to copy or repeat something. The text focuses on how Inca emperors reinforced their claims to imperial authority, not on their copying those claims. Choice B is incorrect because “illuminate” means to clarify or explain. The text is not about explaining the claim to power but about strengthening it. Choice D is incorrect because “rescind” means to withdraw or cancel. It would make no sense for an emperor seeking to rule an empire to rescind his claim to imperial authority, when the context emphasizes defending that authority.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'To demonstrate that collisions between black holes could be detected from over a billion light-years away, physicist Gabriela González and colleagues on the LIGO Scientific Collaboration _______ the fact that massive accelerating bodies produce gravitational waves: the team showed that minuscule distortions in spacetime, smaller than a proton’s diameter, could be measured with laser interferometry and used to confirm a major prediction of Einstein’s general theory of relativity. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"hypothesized"},{"id":"B","text":"discounted"},{"id":"C","text":"redefined"},{"id":"D","text":"exploited"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of using gravitational-wave physics to detect collisions between black holes from over a billion light-years away. In this context, “exploited” means made productive use of. The text indicates that massive accelerating bodies are known to produce gravitational waves and that González and colleagues showed that the resulting distortions in spacetime—smaller than a proton’s diameter—can be measured with laser interferometry. By relying on this physical fact to demonstrate that such distant collisions can be detected, the researchers made productive use of, or exploited, this property of accelerating massive bodies. Choice A is incorrect because in this context, “hypothesized” would mean made a tentative assumption to be tested in a study or experiment. Although the researchers may have held hypotheses related to gravitational-wave measurement, the text presents the production of gravitational waves by massive accelerating bodies as an established prediction of general relativity, not as an untested assumption. The clause after the colon shows that they were not assessing whether gravitational waves exist, but rather whether such waves can be measured with sufficient precision. Choice B is incorrect because “discounted” would mean downplayed or ignored, but the text suggests the opposite: the fact that accelerating massive bodies produce gravitational waves forms the basis of the team’s detection method. Nothing indicates that González and colleagues dismissed this principle; instead, the text shows that they relied on it to achieve their breakthrough. Choice C is incorrect because “redefined” would imply that the researchers altered or reformulated the understanding of gravitational-wave production. However, the text indicates that their achievement involved detecting and confirming a major prediction of Einstein’s general theory of relativity, not redefining it. The researchers did not propose a new theoretical framework; they demonstrated that an existing prediction could be observed empirically.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from The Wind in the Willows (1908) by Kenneth Grahame. Mole had been working hard all morning, spring-cleaning his little home. Dust lay thick upon the furniture, and after much sweeping and polishing he grew tired of the endless labor. Suddenly, he flung down his brush and scurried up to the fresh air and sunlight of the riverbank, eager for a change of scene and company. As used in the text, what does the phrase “scurried up to” most nearly mean?', '[{"id":"A","text":"accompanied"},{"id":"B","text":"hurried toward"},{"id":"C","text":"peered over at"},{"id":"D","text":"complained about"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because in this context, “scurried up to” describes Mole quickly moving from his underground home to the riverbank. The text indicates that Mole is tired of cleaning and suddenly leaves his home, which logically suggests a rapid, eager movement toward the riverbank. Thus, “hurried toward” best captures the meaning. Choice A is incorrect because “accompanied” means going along with someone, but the text shows Mole leaving alone, not joining another character. Choice C is incorrect because “peered over at” refers to looking intently or searchingly, which does not match the physical movement described. Mole is not simply looking at the riverbank; he is traveling there. Choice D is incorrect because “complained about” refers to expressing dissatisfaction, and although Mole is tired of cleaning, the text does not describe him verbally protesting. Instead, he takes action by quickly heading toward the riverbank.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'According to a team of cognitive psychologists at Stanford University, people’s ability to recognize faces quickly may depend on communication between the fusiform gyrus and the amygdala. Individuals tend to identify faces more accurately when information flow between the regions is enhanced, whereas they make recognition errors more frequently when information flow is _______. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"diminished"},{"id":"B","text":"cataloged"},{"id":"C","text":"predicted"},{"id":"D","text":"acquired"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of how the flow of information between two regions of the brain affects facial recognition. In this context, “diminished” means reduced or weakened. The text presents findings from cognitive psychologists showing that rapid and accurate facial recognition is linked to communication between the fusiform gyrus and the amygdala. The contrast is drawn between people who recognize faces accurately and those who make errors. The context indicates that errors are more frequent when the information flow is decreased. Choice B is incorrect because “cataloged” means organized or listed, which does not make sense in context. The text concerns the rate of information transfer between brain regions, not the organization of data. Choice C is incorrect because “predicted” means anticipated or forecasted, which is unrelated to the described neural communication. Choice D is incorrect because “acquired” means obtained or gained, which is not consistent with the context describing reduced information flow between the brain regions.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Claims about the symbolic meaning of Indus Valley seals—engraved with animals, humans, and abstract motifs around 2500 BCE—are difficult to successfully _______. Archaeologists have not deciphered the Indus script, and the cultural context of these seals remains largely unknown, so any interpretation inevitably relies on conjecture. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"corroborate"},{"id":"B","text":"defend"},{"id":"C","text":"simplify"},{"id":"D","text":"embellish"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Indus Valley seals. In this context, “defend” means support in the face of argument. The text emphasizes that scholars know very little about the Indus Valley Civilization, including the script and cultural practices associated with the seals. As a result, any claims about the meaning of the seals are difficult to substantiate and are likely based on speculation, making “defend” the most appropriate choice. Choice A is incorrect because “corroborate” means to confirm with additional evidence. While corroboration is related to support, the text focuses on the difficulty of making claims at all, not the process of confirming them with extra evidence. Choice C is incorrect because “simplify” means to make something less complex. The text does not discuss reducing or clarifying claims about the seals but rather emphasizes that such claims are inherently uncertain. Choice D is incorrect because “embellish” means to add decorative or exaggerated detail. The text does not suggest that scholars are exaggerating or decorating their claims; rather, it emphasizes the challenge of making any claim that can be reasonably supported.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Though not closely related, the marsupial sugar gliders of Australia share basic _______ true flying squirrels, including gliding membranes, large eyes adapted for nocturnal activity, and small, lightweight bodies—traits the two groups of mammals independently developed in response to analogous ecological niches. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"evidence of"},{"id":"B","text":"similarities with"},{"id":"C","text":"substitutes for"},{"id":"D","text":"instances of"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because in context, sharing “similarities with” means having some resemblance to. The text establishes a comparison between two groups of mammals, stating that although sugar gliders and flying squirrels are not closely related, they occupy similar ecological niches, which has led to the independent development of comparable physical traits. This context supports the idea that sugar gliders resemble, or share basic similarities with, true flying squirrels in some respects. Choice A is incorrect because the text doesn’t suggest that sugar gliders are “evidence of” flying squirrels. The focus is on traits shared due to convergent evolution, not on one being proof of the other. Choice C is incorrect because “substitutes for” would mean replacing or acting in place of. The text doesn’t suggest that sugar gliders serve as replacements for flying squirrels, only that they share certain adaptations. Choice D is incorrect because “instances of” would imply that sugar gliders are examples of flying squirrels, which the text explicitly refutes by noting that the two groups are not closely related.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In literary historian John Clute’s survey of speculative fiction, he notes a discernible shift during the 1980s toward _______ postmodern experimentation, contrasting with the more structurally conventional narratives produced by genre writers from the 1950s through the early 1970s. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"a tentatively"},{"id":"B","text":"a rigorously"},{"id":"C","text":"a cordially"},{"id":"D","text":"an inadvertently"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Clute’s survey. In this context, “rigorously” means in a thorough or methodical way. The text draws a contrast between the experimental, boundary-pushing nature of postmodern narratives in the 1980s and the more conventional, formulaic storytelling of the 1950s–1970s. This contrast implies that the postmodern experimentation Clute notes was deliberate, systematic, and structurally complex. Choice A is incorrect because “tentatively” would imply hesitation or uncertainty, which contradicts the text’s description of a clear and discernible shift toward experimentation. Choice C is incorrect because “cordially” would suggest friendliness or politeness, which is irrelevant to the literary shift described. Choice D is incorrect because “inadvertently” would suggest unintentional experimentation, whereas the text frames the 1980s postmodern experimentation as deliberate and recognizable.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Harper Lee’s To Kill a Mockingbird (1960). The narrator is reflecting on a conversation with Atticus Finch, who is explaining how to understand people better. He suggests that one cannot truly comprehend another person’s thoughts or actions without imagining oneself in their situation. “You never really understand a person until you consider things from his point of view … until you climb into his skin and walk around in it.” As used in the text, what does the phrase “climb into his skin and walk around in it” most nearly mean?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To imitate someone’s behavior"},{"id":"B","text":"To experience someone else’s perspective"},{"id":"C","text":"To judge someone’s actions"},{"id":"D","text":"To adopt someone’s physical traits"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because as used in the text, “climb into his skin and walk around in it” most nearly means to experience someone else’s perspective. The narrator emphasizes empathy, suggesting that understanding a person requires imagining oneself in their circumstances and seeing the world as they see it. Choice A is incorrect because the passage is not advocating imitation; it is about understanding, not copying behavior. Choice C is incorrect because “judging someone’s actions” implies evaluation or criticism, whereas the passage emphasizes comprehension without judgment. Choice D is incorrect because the text is metaphorical; it does not refer to literally adopting someone’s physical traits.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The works of Mexican artist Frida Kahlo are now _______ in museums around the world, but the murals she collaborated on with Diego Rivera early in her career were installed in public buildings across Mexico City. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"invented"},{"id":"B","text":"adjusted"},{"id":"C","text":"featured"},{"id":"D","text":"recommended"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Frida Kahlo’s art. In this context, “featured” means shown prominently. The passage focuses on where Kahlo’s works have been and continue to be displayed, contrasting her early murals in public buildings with her paintings now prominently exhibited in museums worldwide. The context therefore supports the idea that Kahlo’s works are currently shown, or featured, in museum settings. Choice A is incorrect because “invented” would mean created for the first time, which is not the focus of the passage; the sentence discusses display, not creation. Choice B is incorrect because “adjusted” would imply that her works were modified or adapted, which the passage does not indicate. Choice D is incorrect because “recommended” would suggest endorsement or suggestion for viewing; while museums select works they value, the passage emphasizes actual display locations rather than reasons for exhibiting them.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Whether Ai Weiwei is producing small-scale sculptures or large public installations—such as Sunflower Seeds, a vast installation at the Tate Modern in London—he is _______ personal experience and social observation, drawing from his upbringing in Beijing and his experiences with political activism in China. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"complemented by"},{"id":"B","text":"uncertain about"},{"id":"C","text":"unbothered by"},{"id":"D","text":"inspired by"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Ai Weiwei’s artistic process. In this context, “inspired by” means influenced or motivated by. The passage emphasizes that, regardless of the scale of his work, Ai Weiwei draws on his personal experiences and social observations to inform his sculptures and installations. This context thus supports the idea that his art is inspired by his upbringing in Beijing and his engagement with political activism. Choice A is incorrect because it would not make logical sense to indicate that Ai Weiwei is “complemented by”—or enhanced by—something inanimate such as personal experience; the focus is on influence, not enhancement. Choice B is incorrect because describing Ai Weiwei as “uncertain about”—or unsure of—his personal experiences would contradict the text, which highlights that he actively draws from them in his art. Choice C is incorrect because “unbothered by”—or indifferent to—his experiences would imply that they have no influence on his creative work, which is the opposite of what the passage conveys.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'John Muir, a naturalist and early advocate for the preservation of wilderness in the United States, undoubtedly influenced the conservation movement, but his legacy in public awareness is perhaps more _______ than that of Rachel Carson, whose book Silent Spring galvanized widespread environmental reform. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"permanent"},{"id":"B","text":"tentative"},{"id":"C","text":"warranted"},{"id":"D","text":"prominent"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of John Muir and Rachel Carson. In this context, “tentative” means unsettled or not definite. The text indicates a contrast between Muir and Carson in terms of their recognition in public awareness (“legacy in public awareness”) and notes that Carson’s Silent Spring “galvanized widespread environmental reform,” making her widely remembered. This context suggests that although Muir had a substantial influence on conservation, his legacy may be less firmly established in popular memory—in other words, more tentative than Carson’s. Choice A is incorrect because the text establishes a contrast between Muir and Carson, so describing Muir’s legacy as “permanent” would contradict the contrast, suggesting that both are equally enduring in memory. Choice C is incorrect because “warranted,” or justified, does not address the degree or clarity of Muir’s recognition in public memory, which is the focus of the sentence. Choice D is incorrect because “prominent” suggests Muir’s legacy is widely recognized, which would conflict with the contrast drawn in the sentence emphasizing that Carson is more widely remembered.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'On the basis of decades of linguistic analysis, researchers in the 1980s hypothesized that the sudden emergence of creole languages in the Caribbean resulted from the blending of African and European grammatical systems. This _______ was supported by field studies conducted in the 2000s, which documented structural patterns consistent across multiple creole languages. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"hypothesis"},{"id":"B","text":"observation"},{"id":"C","text":"invariant"},{"id":"D","text":"trial"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the 1980s linguistic work on creole languages. In this context, a “hypothesis” is a proposed explanation based on analysis and reasoning. The text states that researchers predicted that creole languages emerged through a blending of grammatical systems, drawing on their analysis of linguistic data over decades. This prediction was later supported by field studies, indicating that it was a well-founded hypothesis—a proposed explanation that could be confirmed through further research. Choice B is incorrect because “observation” refers to noticing or recording phenomena. The text indicates that researchers made a prediction or explanation before later supporting evidence was gathered; the idea itself was not merely an observation. Choice C is incorrect because “invariant” refers to something that does not change. The text discusses a proposed explanation for language emergence, not a factor or property that is unchanging. Choice D is incorrect because “trial” implies a controlled test or experiment. While field studies later confirmed the hypothesis, the original prediction was a theoretical proposition rather than an experimental trial.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Maria Nhambu’s Africa''s Child. Nhambu reflects on her experience of life and imagination. “I marveled at the beauty of all life and savored the power and possibilities of my imagination. In these rare moments, I prayed, I danced, and I analyzed. I saw that life was good and bad, beautiful and ugly. I understood that I had to dwell on the good and beautiful in order to keep my imagination, sensitivity, and gratitude intact. I knew it would not be easy to maintain this perspective. I knew I would often twist and turn, bend and crack a little, but I also knew that…I would never completely break.” As used in the text, what does the word “dwell” most nearly mean?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Live in a place"},{"id":"B","text":"Focus attention on"},{"id":"C","text":"Avoid"},{"id":"D","text":"Write about"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because as used in the text, “dwell” most nearly means to focus attention on or give careful consideration to. Nhambu states that she “had to dwell on the good and beautiful in order to keep [her] imagination, sensitivity, and gratitude intact,” suggesting that she needed to consciously think about and attend to positive aspects of life. Choice A is incorrect. In some contexts, “dwell” can mean to reside in a physical location, but here Nhambu is describing a mental or emotional action, not a physical place. Choice C is incorrect. “Avoiding” is the opposite of the meaning implied in the passage, since she emphasizes actively attending to the good and beautiful. Choice D is incorrect. While “writing about” can sometimes be associated with dwelling on something in a figurative sense, the passage clearly refers to mental focus and emotional attention, not literal writing.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the early 1900s, many African American children in the segregated South had limited access to quality education. To _______ this situation, Mary McLeod Bethune founded the Daytona Normal and Industrial School for Negro Girls in 1904, providing students with academic instruction and vocational training that empowered generations of young women. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"perpetuate"},{"id":"B","text":"remedy"},{"id":"C","text":"maintain"},{"id":"D","text":"illustrate"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of how Mary McLeod Bethune addressed the lack of educational opportunities for African American children in the segregated South in the early twentieth century. In this context, “remedy” means to correct or improve an undesirable situation. The text indicates that by founding the Daytona Normal and Industrial School for Negro Girls in 1904, Bethune took action to provide students with academic and vocational training. This context supports the idea that she aimed to remedy the educational inequities affecting these children. Choice A is incorrect because in this context, “perpetuate” would mean to continue or prolong a situation. The text indicates that Bethune actively worked to improve access to education, not to continue the existing lack of opportunities. Choice C is incorrect because “maintain” means to keep something in its current state. According to the text, Bethune sought to change the status quo, providing educational opportunities rather than maintaining the limited access that already existed. Choice D is incorrect because “illustrate” means to demonstrate or show something. The text indicates that Bethune took concrete action to correct the problem, not merely draw attention to it.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Longitudinal ecological investigations of forest succession occasionally fail to _______ prognostications formulated by conservationists predicated on ephemeral field observations. One explanation for this divergence is that short-term assessments may neglect latent influences of edaphic conditions, climatic oscillations, or interspecific interactions that shape arboreal development over protracted temporal scales. (check this for corrections) Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"circumvent"},{"id":"B","text":"corroborate"},{"id":"C","text":"disseminate"},{"id":"D","text":"implement"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of a relationship between long-term ecological studies of forest succession and predictions made by conservationists based on short-term observations. In this context, “corroborate” means to confirm or support with evidence. The text indicates that short-term assessments may overlook factors like soil conditions, climatic variation, or species interactions that affect tree growth over decades. Therefore, long-term ecological studies may produce results that do not align with—or fail to corroborate—conservationists’ initial predictions. Choice A is incorrect because it wouldn’t make sense to say that the studies could “circumvent,” or bypass, the predictions; studies cannot deliberately avoid something. Choice C is incorrect because “disseminate” means to spread or distribute information. The text is concerned with whether the studies confirm the predictions, not with distributing them. Choice D is incorrect because “implement” means to put something into effect. Ecological studies cannot implement predictions; they can only provide evidence supporting or failing to support them.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Alpine plants often survive in extreme high-altitude environments that are inhospitable to most other species. Their physiological adaptations allow them to _______ lowland species that might tolerate occasional frost but cannot endure the prolonged cold, high UV exposure, and nutrient-poor soils characteristic of alpine zones. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"distinguished from"},{"id":"B","text":"assimilated into"},{"id":"C","text":"conflated with"},{"id":"D","text":"derived from"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of alpine plants. In this context, “distinguished from” means recognized as different or set apart from. The text indicates that alpine plants are adapted to survive extreme high-altitude conditions, whereas lowland species may tolerate only occasional frost and cannot endure prolonged cold, high UV exposure, or poor soils. Therefore, alpine plants can be distinguished from lowland species based on these adaptations. Choice B is incorrect because “assimilated into” means incorporated into something else. The text does not suggest that alpine plants merge with lowland species. Choice C is incorrect because “conflated with” means combined or treated as the same. The passage emphasizes differences between alpine and lowland species, so conflating them would contradict the text. Choice D is incorrect because “derived from” implies that alpine plants originate from lowland species. The text focuses on ecological and physiological distinctions, not evolutionary derivation.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the late 1800s, bicycles were a costly and exclusive mode of transportation. The advent of the safety bicycle, featuring equidimensional wheels and a chain-driven rear sprocket, served to _______ cycling: it rendered the activity practicable, widely attainable, and socially embraced, and soon engendered the proliferation of cycling clubs and competitive races. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"hinder"},{"id":"B","text":"glorify"},{"id":"C","text":"popularize"},{"id":"D","text":"sequester"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the safety bicycle. To “popularize” an activity is to make it widely accessible and appreciated. The text indicates that the safety bicycle made cycling practicable and attainable for a broad range of people and contributed to the rapid growth of cycling clubs and races. Therefore, the safety bicycle helped popularize cycling. Choice A is incorrect because the text indicates that the safety bicycle expanded access to cycling, not hindered it. Choice B is incorrect because although cycling may have been celebrated, the text emphasizes accessibility and adoption, not mere praise. Choice D is incorrect because the text shows that cycling became more widely practiced, not sequestered or limited to an exclusive group.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Sculptor Isamu Noguchi often drew inspiration from the natural forms of rocks and water. The shapes and textures he observed in his surroundings _______ his sculptural designs. For instance, Noguchi’s abstract forms frequently mimic the smooth curves of river stones and the undulating lines of sand dunes. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"inhibited"},{"id":"B","text":"influenced"},{"id":"C","text":"contradicted"},{"id":"D","text":"concealed"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of sculptor Isamu Noguchi’s work. In this context, “influenced” means to have affected or shaped the development of something. The text indicates that Noguchi’s observation of natural forms like rocks and water had a direct impact on his sculptural designs, giving the example of his abstract forms mimicking curves of river stones and sand dunes. Choice A is incorrect because the text conveys that Noguchi’s surroundings inspired and guided his work, rather than inhibiting, or preventing, it. Choice C is incorrect because the natural shapes did not oppose or contradict Noguchi’s designs; they served as inspiration. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not suggest that rocks and water obscured or hid Noguchi’s creative ideas; rather, they helped shape them.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the early 2000s, ecologists initiated a large-scale reintroduction program for the European pond turtle, releasing hundreds of hatchlings into restored wetland habitats. This strategy proved _______: within two decades, the turtle population in the monitored sites increased steadily, indicating that the program effectively bolstered the species’ numbers. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"ineffectual"},{"id":"B","text":"profitable"},{"id":"C","text":"efficacious"},{"id":"D","text":"detrimental"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the ecologists’ turtle reintroduction program. In this context, “efficacious” means producing the desired effect or outcome. The text indicates that ecologists released hundreds of European pond turtle hatchlings into restored wetland habitats to increase the population. The following sentence notes that the population “increased steadily,” which shows that the strategy achieved its intended goal. Therefore, the program was efficacious because it successfully bolstered the species’ numbers. Choice A is incorrect because “ineffectual” means failing to produce the desired effect, which contradicts the text’s statement that the population increased steadily. Choice B is incorrect because “profitable” refers to generating financial gain, which is not relevant to the context of a conservation program aimed at population growth. Choice D is incorrect because “detrimental” means harmful or damaging, which contradicts the text’s description of the program as increasing the turtle population.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1993, astronomers observed SN 1993J, a peculiar Type IIb supernova, that exhibited remarkably strong and long-lived X‑ray emission, _______ for a supernova of its type. Typical Type II explosions usually display much lower X-ray luminosity over comparable time scales. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"conventional"},{"id":"B","text":"anomalous"},{"id":"C","text":"predictable"},{"id":"D","text":"routine"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of SN 1993J’s unusual X-ray emission. In this context, “anomalous” refers to something that deviates from what is standard or expected. The text explains that SN 1993J had remarkably strong and long-lived X-ray emission, whereas typical Type II supernovae exhibit much lower X-ray luminosity over similar time scales. This contrast indicates that SN 1993J’s behavior was unusual for its type, making it anomalous. Choice A is incorrect because “conventional” implies that SN 1993J’s behavior was typical or expected, which the text explicitly contradicts. Choice C is incorrect because “predictable” suggests the X-ray emission would follow expected patterns, but SN 1993J’s emission was exceptional and not predictable from other Type II supernovae. Choice D is incorrect because “routine” implies normal or ordinary, but the text emphasizes that SN 1993J’s X-ray emission deviated substantially from the standard behavior of its type.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1905, Albert Einstein traveled to several European universities to present his early work on the theory of relativity. His reputation as a brilliant thinker preceded him. This _______ likely aided him in gaining the attention and respect of prominent physicists across the continent. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"notoriety"},{"id":"B","text":"acclaim"},{"id":"C","text":"skepticism"},{"id":"D","text":"candor"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Albert Einstein’s early reputation. In this context, “acclaim” means high praise or recognition. The text indicates that Einstein’s reputation as a brilliant thinker preceded him, suggesting that his recognized brilliance helped him gain the attention and respect of other physicists. Choice B fits this context perfectly. Choice A is incorrect because “notoriety” typically carries a negative connotation of fame for undesirable reasons, which contradicts the text’s implication that Einstein’s reputation was positive and beneficial. Choice C is incorrect because “skepticism” implies doubt or disbelief, which does not align with the text’s suggestion that Einstein’s reputation helped him gain attention and respect. Choice D is incorrect because “candor” refers to honesty or straightforwardness; although a positive trait, the text emphasizes the effect of Einstein’s pre-existing reputation rather than his personal manner, so “candor” does not logically complete the sentence.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1920, Warren G. Harding became the 29th president of the United States. Despite a relatively brief tenure in office (1921–1923), Harding emerged as one of the most ______ figures in early twentieth-century American politics: his administration implemented key post–World War I policies and attempted to stabilize the economy, even as scandals later came to light. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"obscure"},{"id":"B","text":"Inconsequential"},{"id":"C","text":"influential"},{"id":"D","text":"reticent"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Harding. In this context, “influential” means having a notable effect or impact. The text indicates that Harding, despite his relatively brief tenure, implemented important post–World War I policies and attempted to stabilize the economy, which demonstrates that he was a consequential figure in American politics. Choice A is incorrect because “obscure” would suggest Harding was unknown or unimportant, which contradicts the text emphasizing his policy actions and impact. Choice B is incorrect because “inconsequential” implies his actions had little effect, which conflicts with the text’s discussion of his influence on the economy and political landscape. Choice D is incorrect because “reticent” refers to being reserved or unwilling to speak, which is irrelevant to the discussion of Harding’s political significance.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1905, Albert Einstein traveled to several European universities to present his early work on the theory of relativity. His reputation as a brilliant thinker preceded him. This _______ likely aided him in gaining the attention and respect of prominent physicists across the continent. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"notoriety"},{"id":"B","text":"acclaim"},{"id":"C","text":"skepticism"},{"id":"D","text":"candor"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Albert Einstein’s early reputation. In this context, “acclaim” means high praise or recognition. The text indicates that Einstein’s reputation as a brilliant thinker preceded him, suggesting that his recognized brilliance helped him gain the attention and respect of other physicists. Choice B fits this context perfectly. Choice A is incorrect because “notoriety” typically carries a negative connotation of fame for undesirable reasons, which contradicts the text’s implication that Einstein’s reputation was positive and beneficial. Choice C is incorrect because “skepticism” implies doubt or disbelief, which does not align with the text’s suggestion that Einstein’s reputation helped him gain attention and respect. Choice D is incorrect because “candor” refers to honesty or straightforwardness; although a positive trait, the text emphasizes the effect of Einstein’s pre-existing reputation rather than his personal manner, so “candor” does not logically complete the sentence.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Mangrove swamps line many tropical coastlines and provide dense root systems that extend into shallow waters. These root networks offer protection for juvenile fish, crabs, and other aquatic organisms by reducing wave energy and water turbulence. In this way, mangrove swamps create a more _______ habitat in which young animals can feed and grow safely. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"chaotic"},{"id":"B","text":"sheltered"},{"id":"C","text":"elaborate"},{"id":"D","text":"harsh"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of how mangrove swamps help juvenile aquatic organisms. In this context, “sheltered” means protected from danger or harsh conditions. The text explains that the mangrove root networks reduce wave energy and water turbulence, creating areas where young animals can feed and grow safely. Choice A is incorrect because “chaotic” means disorderly or turbulent, which is the opposite of what the text describes—the mangrove roots reduce turbulence rather than create it. Choice C is incorrect because “elaborate” means intricate or detailed, which doesn’t address the calm or protective quality of the habitat. Choice D is incorrect because “harsh” suggests dangerous or difficult conditions, whereas the text emphasizes that mangrove swamps provide a safer environment for juvenile animals.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1928, the novel The Well of Loneliness by Radclyffe Hall became one of the most prominent examples of ______ in literature. Few authors of the period addressed issues of sexual identity so openly, and the resulting controversy demonstrates how unusual Hall’s work was. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"allegory"},{"id":"B","text":"collaboration"},{"id":"C","text":"advocacy"},{"id":"D","text":"censorship"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it logically and precisely completes the text’s discussion of Hall’s novel. In this context, “advocacy” means expressing support for a marginalized group—in this case, for sexual identity and LGBTQ+ experiences. The text indicates that few authors addressed sexual identity so openly at the time, and Hall’s novel drew attention and controversy precisely because it advocated for issues rarely discussed in literature. Choice A is incorrect because “allegory” refers to a symbolic story, but the text focuses on the social and literary impact of the novel, not symbolic storytelling. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not indicate that the novel was written collaboratively; it emphasizes Hall’s singular work and the cultural significance of her subject matter. Choice D is incorrect because “censorship” refers to the suppression of content, and while Hall’s novel did face censorship, the blank calls for a term describing the nature or significance of the literary work itself, not the external response to it.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Marie Tharp’s contributions to oceanography are _______: she not only generated the inaugural cartographic syntheses of the oceanic abyssal plains but also provided pivotal empirical corroboration for the theory of plate tectonics, thereby irrevocably transforming scientific paradigms regarding Earth’s geodynamic processes. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"modest"},{"id":"B","text":"peripheral"},{"id":"C","text":"monumental"},{"id":"D","text":"negligible"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of Marie Tharp’s contributions to oceanography. In this context, “monumental” means exceptionally important, influential, or significant. The text indicates that Tharp’s work included creating the first detailed maps of the ocean floor and providing crucial evidence supporting plate tectonics, fundamentally changing scientific understanding of Earth’s geodynamics. These achievements demonstrate that her contributions were indeed monumental. Choice A is incorrect because the text emphasizes Tharp’s groundbreaking work and transformative influence; “modest,” meaning small or unassuming, contradicts this description. Choice B is incorrect because “peripheral,” meaning minor or on the edge, does not fit the context of Tharp’s central, paradigm-shifting contributions. Choice D is incorrect because “negligible,” meaning insignificant or unimportant, is directly opposed to the text’s depiction of Tharp’s influential work.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In arid desert ecosystems, cacti, small shrubs, and desert-dwelling animals form an _______ system of interdependence: cacti provide shade and retain moisture in the soil; small shrubs offer shelter for insects and reptiles; and animals such as birds and rodents disperse seeds, facilitating plant reproduction. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"superficial"},{"id":"B","text":"intricate"},{"id":"C","text":"redundant"},{"id":"D","text":"ornamental"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of desert ecosystems. In this context, “intricate” means composed of many interconnected and interdependent parts. The text details how plants and animals in deserts rely on one another—cacti provide shade and water retention, shrubs offer shelter, and animals disperse seeds—indicating a complex, interconnected system. Choice A is incorrect because “superficial,” meaning shallow or simple, would not reflect the elaborate ecological interactions described. Choice C is incorrect because “redundant,” meaning repetitive or unnecessary, does not match the purposeful interdependence of the species described. Choice D is incorrect because “ornamental,” meaning decorative, would suggest aesthetic value rather than functional ecological relationships.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In certain species of deep-sea squid, some individuals possess a small, seemingly vestigial photophore along the edge of their mantle. Given that this photophore is more common in squids living at greater depths, some marine biologists suggest that its function is not _______; instead, it may actively contribute to camouflage or communication in the deep ocean. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"incidental"},{"id":"B","text":"arbitrary"},{"id":"C","text":"dormant"},{"id":"D","text":"redundant"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion of the deep-sea squid photophore. In this context, “dormant” means inactive or without apparent function. The text sets up a contrast between the assumption that the photophore has no function and the evidence suggesting that it may aid in camouflage or signaling. This conveys that the photophore is not merely dormant but may have an active role in survival. Choice A is incorrect because “incidental,” meaning occurring by chance, would not capture the idea of the photophore being thought functionless yet potentially important. Choice B is incorrect because “arbitrary,” meaning random or capricious, does not make sense in the context of an organ possibly serving a biological function. Choice D is incorrect because “redundant,” meaning unnecessary or superfluous, is opposite to the idea that the photophore may in fact have a purposeful role.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The traditional method of producing synthetic textiles often relies on energy-intensive chemical treatments, making the process _______ due to its high carbon footprint and significant water consumption. Recent advances in green textile chemistry, however, have enabled production techniques that minimize environmental impact while maintaining fiber quality. Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', '[{"id":"A","text":"exemplary"},{"id":"B","text":"unsustainable"},{"id":"C","text":"innovative"},{"id":"D","text":"negligible"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most logically completes the text’s discussion about traditional synthetic textile production. In this context, “unsustainable” means not able to be maintained without causing harm or depleting resources. The text indicates that the traditional process consumes excessive energy and water and has a high carbon footprint, which conveys that it is environmentally harmful and therefore unsustainable. Choice A is incorrect because “exemplary” would suggest the process is a model of good practice, which contradicts the text’s emphasis on negative environmental effects. Choice C is incorrect because “innovative” would suggest the process is new and creative, but the text describes it as traditional and problematic, not pioneering. Choice D is incorrect because “negligible” would imply the environmental impact is minimal, which is the opposite of what the text conveys.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Jane Austen’s 1811 novel Sense and Sensibility. The speaker, the narrator, describes the early conversation between Elinor and a young man, as they discover shared tastes in leisure and literature. Mention any favourite amusement to engage her to talk. She could not be silent when such points were introduced, and she had neither shyness nor reserve in their discussion. They speedily discovered that their enjoyment of dancing and music was mutual, and that it arose from a general conformity of judgment in all that related to either. Encouraged by this to a further examination of his opinions, she proceeded to question him on the subject of books; her favourite authors were brought forward and dwelt upon with so rapturous a delight that any young man of five and twenty must have been insensible indeed not to become an immediate convert to the excellence of such works, however disregarded before. Their taste was strikingly alike. The same books, the same passages were idolized by each; or if any difference appeared, any objection arose, it lasted no longer than till the force of her arguments and the brightness of her eyes could be displayed. He acquiesced in all her decisions, caught all her enthusiasm; and long before his visit concluded, they conversed with the familiarity of a long-established acquaintance. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To show that the young man quickly becomes aligned with her tastes and opinions through shared interests and her enthusiasm"},{"id":"B","text":"To clarify that the young man initially disagreed with her but gradually learned to tolerate her viewpoints"},{"id":"C","text":"To elaborate on the idea that the young woman’s friends generally lacked knowledge of her favourite authors"},{"id":"D","text":"To assert that their discussions required formal guidance to reach agreement"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately portrays the main purpose of the text. At the beginning of the passage, the narrator emphasizes how the young man and Elinor share mutual enjoyment of dancing and music, which naturally extends to literature. The young man is captivated by her enthusiasm and arguments, acquiescing in her decisions and adopting her tastes. Overall, the main purpose of the passage is to convey how shared interests and her engaging manner lead to immediate alignment of their preferences and opinions. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not suggest that he merely tolerates her opinions; rather, he actively embraces them. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not critique the knowledge of her friends; it focuses on the mutuality between her and the young man. Choice D is incorrect because no formal guidance is mentioned; their agreement arises naturally through conversation and shared enthusiasm.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The field of chronobiology examines how internal biological clocks regulate daily rhythms in living organisms. In mammals, for instance, a cluster of neurons in the brain’s suprachiasmatic nucleus helps synchronize hormone release, sleep, and body temperature to external daylight cues. Researchers long assumed that such regulation required a centralized neural system, but recent studies by marine biologist Kristin Tessmar-Raible and her team suggest otherwise: they have documented that bristle worms, simple invertebrates without a comparable brain structure, also rely on light-sensitive molecular feedback loops to coordinate reproductive and migratory cycles with lunar illumination patterns. What choice best describes the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. It explains a new laboratory method for measuring changes in the circadian rhythms of marine organisms."},{"id":"B","text":"B. It describes research indicating that certain invertebrates use mechanisms for biological timekeeping that function without a centralized neural clock."},{"id":"C","text":"C. It presents evidence that some animals are more sensitive to lunar cycles than to solar cycles."},{"id":"D","text":"D. It illustrates how disruptions to natural light cycles can interfere with migration and reproduction in ocean species."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because the passage’s primary purpose is to summarize research suggesting that some invertebrates (specifically bristle worms) use light-dependent molecular feedback loops to regulate biological rhythms without the centralized neural clock found in mammals. Just as the sample passage compared insect dopamine processes to mammalian ones, this text compares a decentralized timing mechanism in worms to the centralized structure in mammals, highlighting a potential similarity in function despite organizational differences. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not describe a laboratory method, measurement technique, or experimental procedure. Instead, it describes biological mechanisms and the findings of Tessmar-Raible’s research team. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not argue that bristle worms are more sensitive to lunar cycles than solar cycles—only that the worms’ routines are coordinated with lunar illumination. No comparative claim of degree or exclusivity is made. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss disruptions or ecological consequences. It simply presents evidence that bristle worms possess a timing system previously thought to require complex neural structures, not the environmental impact of altered light conditions.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Since 2010, several West African countries have introduced national programs that integrate endangered local languages into primary school curricula, aiming to preserve linguistic heritage through state-supported education. In contrast, communities in New Zealand and the United States have often relied on community-driven “language nests” and immersion schools—initiatives started by speakers themselves rather than by government ministries—to revitalize Māori and Native American languages. These differing models have both led to increases in the number of young fluent speakers, though through distinct institutional pathways. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To describe how government-led language revitalization efforts have spread from West Africa to other regions of the world"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To compare two broad strategies that different communities use to preserve endangered languages"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To argue that community-led language preservation models are more effective than government-backed initiatives"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To explain why some countries have failed to maintain linguistic diversity despite increased governmental funding"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately captures the text’s main purpose: to compare two distinct strategies used in different parts of the world to preserve endangered languages. The text first describes government-initiated curriculum programs in West Africa, then contrasts them with community-driven immersion programs in New Zealand and the United States. This structure makes clear that the core purpose is to highlight two different but successful approaches to language revitalization. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not claim that West African initiatives have influenced or “spread” to other regions. Instead, it contrasts independent developments in different places. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not argue that one approach is better. It explicitly notes that both strategies “have…led to increases in the number of young fluent speakers,” showing neither superiority nor advocacy. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss failure or decline in linguistic diversity, nor does it mention insufficient success in any country. The focus is on successful revitalization models, not unsuccessful ones.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Tardigrades—microscopic invertebrates known for surviving extreme conditions—were long believed to be highly vulnerable to cellular damage during severe dehydration, since the loss of water typically causes proteins to unfold and membranes to become unstable. However, recent studies by Thomas Boothby and colleagues demonstrated that tardigrades employ a unique set of intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs) called CAHS proteins, which form protective, glass-like matrices inside cells as the organism dries out. These matrices stabilize cellular components and prevent the damage scientists once assumed was unavoidable. Furthermore, even when dehydration is prolonged, researchers found that tardigrades can reverse much of this stress by rapidly rehydrating, allowing the CAHS matrices to dissolve and normal cellular activity to resume. Which choice best describes the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To call for additional research into how dehydration affects the long-term evolution of tardigrade species"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To discuss a conclusion drawn in a study examining how CAHS proteins protect tardigrade DNA from radiation exposure"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To explain behavioral adaptations that help tardigrades avoid exposure to extreme environmental stress"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To present findings that challenge a previously held assumption about tardigrades’ susceptibility to dehydration-induced cellular damage"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most accurately describes the main purpose of the text, which is to present findings that challenge a prior assumption about tardigrades’ vulnerability to dehydration-related cellular damage. The text introduces the concern that dehydration typically destabilizes cells by causing proteins to unfold and membranes to deteriorate. It then describes research showing that tardigrades can avoid this damage through CAHS proteins, and that they can recover even after prolonged dehydration. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not call for further research or suggest that more studies are needed on tardigrade evolution. Instead, it focuses on current findings that explain why tardigrades may not be as susceptible to dehydration as previously believed. Choice B is incorrect because the study described in the text does not investigate DNA protection from radiation. According to the passage, the research addresses how CAHS proteins stabilize cellular components during dehydration. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not discuss behavioral strategies tardigrades use to avoid harsh conditions. Rather, it explains physiological mechanisms that protect them from cellular damage during dehydration.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 2023, marine biologist Danelle Cline and her team at the Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute released FathomNet, the first large-scale, open-source training dataset designed specifically for automated identification of deep-sea organisms. Traditional image datasets used for machine-learning research rarely include deep-ocean species, making it difficult for researchers to build accurate image-recognition tools for marine science. FathomNet, however, was created by combining expert-annotated footage from deep-sea robots with contributions from oceanographers worldwide. By merging marine taxonomy with computer-vision standards, the project offers a novel model for how scientific data can be organized, annotated, and shared across disciplines. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To evaluate whether machine-learning systems can outperform human biologists in species identification"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To present one researcher’s concerns about gaps in existing marine-biology datasets"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To explain why a particular scientific dataset represents a significant innovation"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To describe how researchers train underwater robots to capture usable deep-sea images"}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because the text highlights what makes FathomNet particularly innovative. It explains that traditional datasets lack deep-sea organisms and describes how Cline’s project combines expert-annotated robot footage with global scientific contributions to create a new, interdisciplinary data model. The focus is on what makes this dataset unique and groundbreaking. Choice A is incorrect because the text never compares machine-learning systems to human biologists. It discusses dataset creation, not performance evaluation. Choice B is incorrect because although the text notes limitations in existing datasets, it does not present one researcher’s concerns or opinions. Instead, it emphasizes a new solution. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not describe how underwater robots are trained or how they capture images; it only mentions that their footage was used in the dataset.', 'craft-structure', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the early twentieth century, African American newspapers played a central role in shaping public discourse in major U.S. cities. The Chicago Defender, founded in 1905, quickly became one of the most influential Black newspapers in the country, publishing investigative pieces, political commentary, and cultural reporting. In New York, magazines connected to the Harlem Renaissance—such as The Crisis (established in 1910) and Opportunity (established in 1923)—provided platforms for writers, activists, and artists whose work challenged racial injustice. Together, the publications emerging from these cities created a vibrant and influential ecosystem of African American journalism during this era. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To compare the political positions of African American newspapers published in Chicago and New York in the early 1900s"},{"id":"B","text":"To explain that African American newspapers and magazines flourished in the early twentieth century, especially in major cities like Chicago and New York"},{"id":"C","text":"To argue that African American journalism in New York was more culturally significant than that produced in Chicago"},{"id":"D","text":"To describe how African American newspapers of the early 1900s influenced other publications across the United States"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately captures the main purpose of the passage. The text begins by noting that African American newspapers were influential in major U.S. cities in the early twentieth century. It then gives specific examples—The Chicago Defender, The Crisis, and Opportunity—and explains the important roles they played. The text’s emphasis is that these publications represent a flourishing period of African American journalism in cities like Chicago and New York. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not compare political positions or editorial stances of Chicago and New York publications. It simply describes their prominence. Choice C is incorrect because although the passage mentions New York’s cultural magazines, it does not claim they were more significant than Chicago’s newspaper. No hierarchy or evaluative comparison is made. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss how these newspapers influenced other publications nationwide. It describes their significance within their own cities, not their wider impact.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Cellist Yo-Yo Ma is widely admired for performances that seem effortless and deeply intuitive. Audiences often remark on how naturally he moves with the music, as if responding instinctively in the moment. Although Ma is celebrated for this expressive spontaneity, his apparent ease is the product of extensive behind-the-scenes work. Known for his meticulous preparation, Ma studies each piece repeatedly—exploring its structure, history, and emotional possibilities. Even with works he has performed for decades, he returns to the score with fresh eyes, seeking to understand the music anew each time he steps onstage. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To explain how Ma selects which musical traditions he wants to incorporate into his performances"},{"id":"B","text":"To assert that Ma’s seemingly spontaneous performances result from intense and deliberate preparation"},{"id":"C","text":"To describe the kinds of musical scores Ma prefers to analyze closely before performing"},{"id":"D","text":"To argue that Ma’s interpretive style is unusual compared with that of other celebrated cellists"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately captures the main purpose of the passage: to show that Yo-Yo Ma’s performances appear spontaneous only because of the careful preparation behind them. The text begins by noting that Ma seems to respond naturally and instinctively to the music onstage. It then emphasizes the extensive study and repeated examination he undertakes, even for pieces he knows well. These details demonstrate that the goal of the passage is to assert that Ma’s expressive ease is the result of intensive preparation. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not discuss how Ma chooses musical traditions or genres for performance; instead, it focuses on how he prepares music he already plans to perform. Choice C is incorrect because although the passage mentions Ma analyzing pieces closely, it does not specify particular types of scores or indicate that he favors certain kinds over others. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not argue that Ma’s approach is unusual or contrast his methods with those of other cellists. It simply explains how he prepares for performances, not how his preparation differs from others’.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Researchers once widely assumed that the earliest human-made boomerangs—some dating back more than 10,000 years—were designed to return to the thrower. But an aerodynamics engineer sought to test this assumption. Using high-speed wind-tunnel simulations, he analyzed replicas of ancient boomerangs recovered from archaeological sites in Europe and Australia. The tests showed that most of these boomerangs produced stable forward flight rather than the curved, looping paths associated with returning boomerangs. Because the replicas behaved like hunting weapons rather than toys or signaling tools, the engineer concluded that early boomerangs were likely not intended to return to their users. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To present contrasting interpretations of boomerang use in ancient societies"},{"id":"B","text":"To describe an experiment whose results challenge a long-held assumption"},{"id":"C","text":"To explain why aerodynamic tools were essential in early human hunting"},{"id":"D","text":"To argue that modern boomerangs are fundamentally different from ancient ones"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately captures the text’s main purpose: to describe an experiment whose results challenge a long-held assumption. The passage begins by noting that researchers once widely believed that early boomerangs were designed to return to the thrower. It then describes how an aerodynamics engineer used wind-tunnel simulations to test this idea. The results showed that ancient boomerangs flew straight rather than looping back, leading the engineer to question the established assumption. Thus, the text’s purpose is to present an experiment that calls into doubt a previously accepted belief. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not offer competing interpretations or debate among researchers. It discusses only the traditional assumption and the experimental findings that undermine it. Choice C is incorrect because although the experiment suggests ancient boomerangs were hunting tools, the text does not explain why aerodynamic tools were essential to early human hunting or discuss hunting practices more broadly. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not compare ancient and modern boomerangs. It focuses solely on testing an assumption about ancient ones.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Harper Lee’s 1960 novel To Kill a Mockingbird. Scout recalls a moment when her father, Atticus, gives Jem an unusual instruction. “Atticus said to Jem one day, ‘I’d rather you shot at tin cans in the backyard, but I know you’ll go after birds. Shoot all the blue jays you want, if you can hit ’em, but remember it’s a sin to kill a mockingbird.’ That was the only time I ever heard Atticus say it was a sin to do something, and I asked Miss Maudie about it. ‘Your father’s right,’ she said. ‘Mockingbirds don’t do one thing except make music for us to enjoy. They don’t eat up people’s gardens, don’t nest in corn cribs, they don’t do one thing but sing their hearts out for us. That’s why it’s a sin to kill a mockingbird.’” Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To illustrate how Jem develops a newfound interest in outdoor activities"},{"id":"B","text":"To highlight Atticus’s unusual moral warning and its explanation"},{"id":"C","text":"To contrast Atticus’s strict rules with Miss Maudie’s more relaxed beliefs"},{"id":"D","text":"To depict the children’s frustration with the limits placed on their play"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately reflects the main purpose of the text. The excerpt centers on Atticus giving Jem a rare moral instruction—specifically, that killing a mockingbird is a sin—and Scout’s curiosity about why he would say such a thing. Miss Maudie then elaborates, explaining that mockingbirds cause no harm and only create music for people to enjoy. Thus, the passage primarily conveys Atticus’s unusual moral warning and the justification that follows. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not describe Jem developing new interests in outdoor activities. Atticus’s comments refer to shooting targets or birds, but the focus is on the moral principle, not on Jem’s hobbies. Choice C is incorrect because there is no contrast between Atticus and Miss Maudie. Miss Maudie explicitly agrees with him, reinforcing his moral message rather than offering a relaxed or opposing viewpoint. Choice D is incorrect because nothing in the passage suggests that the children feel frustrated or restricted by Atticus’s guidance. Scout’s reaction is curiosity about his moral stance, not irritation.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A research team led by cognitive scientist Helena Wu investigated whether brief exposure to uncertainty could influence how people evaluate unfamiliar information. Participants were divided into two groups before completing a fact-checking task involving ambiguous claims. Members of the experimental group spent several minutes reflecting in writing on a situation in which they felt unsure about an outcome, whereas members of the control group wrote about their daily commute. Wu and her colleagues found that participants who reflected on uncertainty were more likely to withhold judgment and seek additional evidence when assessing the claims, compared with participants in the control group. Which choice best describes the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To demonstrate that uncertainty generally leads individuals to distrust new information"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To explain a research finding and describe the experimental procedure that produced it"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To challenge prevailing assumptions about how people respond to ambiguous claims"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To evaluate the effectiveness of different writing prompts used in cognitive experiments"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the text’s primary purpose is to explain a study’s conclusion and outline how the researchers arrived at that conclusion. The passage first states the finding—that reflecting on uncertainty affected how participants evaluated ambiguous claims—and then details the experimental setup that allowed the researchers to compare the experimental and control groups. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not claim that uncertainty causes distrust; instead, it emphasizes increased caution and evidence-seeking. Choice C is incorrect because, although the findings may have implications for existing assumptions, the text does not explicitly frame the study as a challenge to prevailing views. Choice D is incorrect because the writing prompts are described only to clarify the experimental design, not to assess their effectiveness as techniques in their own right.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1675, Dutch astronomer Maria Margaretha Kirch compiled a detailed catalogue documenting a series of comet observations made at the Berlin Observatory. Commissioned by court astronomers seeking to standardize celestial records, the catalogue drew on Kirch’s own nightly measurements as well as reports from observers across Central Europe. Alongside positional data, Kirch included brief narrative notes describing atmospheric conditions and observational difficulties, integrating empirical records with contextual commentary. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To analyze how collaborative observation reshaped early modern astronomical theory"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To describe a historical scientific catalogue and explain the methods used to produce it"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To argue that narrative accounts were essential to the accuracy of seventeenth-century astronomy"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To compare Kirch’s observational practices with those of other European astronomers"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the text’s purpose is to present a specific historical catalogue and explain how it was created, including who commissioned it, what sources were used, and what kinds of information it contained. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not analyze broader theoretical changes in astronomy. Choice C is incorrect because, although narrative notes are mentioned, the text does not argue that such accounts were essential to accuracy. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not compare Kirch’s practices with those of other astronomers, mentioning others only as contributors to her compilation.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1988, environmental chemist Ellen Swallow Richards began organizing informal meetings in her laboratory for students interested in applying scientific principles to public health. As interest grew, these meetings moved into lecture halls and eventually developed into a formal program focused on sanitation, water quality, and household science. By the mid-1890s, the initiative had gained institutional recognition and broadened its activities to include public lectures and community outreach. More than a century later, the program’s legacy endures in the interdisciplinary field now known as environmental health. Which choice best describes the overall purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To examine the personal beliefs that led Richards to emphasize public health education"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To place Richards’s program within broader environmental reform movements of the nineteenth century"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To explain the specific reasons the program expanded beyond laboratory instruction"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To provide an overview of the origins, development, and continuing influence of Richards’s initiative"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is correct because the text traces the initiative from its informal beginnings through its institutional expansion and concludes by noting its lasting influence, indicating an overall purpose of presenting its founding, evolution, and mission. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not discuss Richards’s personal beliefs or motivations. Choice B is incorrect because, although the program relates to public health, the text does not situate it within wider reform movements. Choice C is incorrect because the expansion beyond laboratory instruction is mentioned but only as one part of a broader historical overview rather than the central focus.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'During the early decades of the twentieth century, women’s colleges expanded rapidly across the northeastern United States. While institutions such as Mount Holyoke and Bryn Mawr were already well established, smaller cities also became centers of women’s higher education. Poughkeepsie, New York, for example, supported multiple women-focused academic programs by 1920. Given the region’s concentration of philanthropic funding and reform-minded educators, it is not surprising that the Northeast emerged as a particularly fertile ground for the growth of women’s colleges. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To contrast women’s colleges in the northeastern United States with those in other regions during the early twentieth century"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To explain that women’s colleges expanded in the early twentieth century, particularly in the northeastern United States"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To argue that philanthropic organizations directly controlled the curricula of women’s colleges in the Northeast"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To describe how graduates of northeastern women’s colleges influenced national education policy"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the text explains that women’s colleges grew during the early twentieth century and emphasizes that this expansion was especially notable in the northeastern United States, supporting that claim with examples and contextual reasons. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not compare northeastern women’s colleges with those in other regions. Choice C is incorrect because, although philanthropic funding is mentioned, the text does not argue that such organizations controlled college curricula. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss graduates’ influence on national education policy, focusing instead on institutional growth and regional concentration.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'For many years, historians have assumed that the rapid spread of printed pamphlets in seventeenth-century Europe was driven mainly by rising literacy rates among the general population. To examine this assumption, one historian analyzed circulation records from several major printing centers and compared them with contemporaneous census data. The records showed that pamphlet distribution increased sharply even in regions where literacy levels remained relatively low. Based on this evidence, the historian concluded that factors such as public readings and informal sharing networks likely played a larger role in pamphlet circulation than literacy growth alone. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To emphasize the importance of pamphlets in shaping political discourse in seventeenth-century Europe"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To describe an investigation whose findings challenge a long-standing explanation"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To compare different methods historians use to study early modern print culture"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To argue that literacy rates in Europe rose more slowly than previously believed"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the text describes a specific investigation and explains how its findings undermine a previously accepted explanation for the spread of printed pamphlets. The passage first presents the long-held assumption about literacy driving pamphlet circulation, then outlines the historian’s analysis, and finally explains how the results cast doubt on that assumption. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not focus on pamphlets’ political impact, only on why they spread. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not compare multiple historical research methods; it describes only one study. Choice D is incorrect because, although literacy rates are mentioned, the text does not argue that they were mismeasured or slower to rise, only that they were insufficient to explain pamphlet distribution.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Susan Glaspell’s 1912 short story At Twilight. The scene describes an old man and a young girl sitting together as evening descends. “They sat there as twilight drew near to night, the old man and the young girl, silent. The laughter of boys and girls and the good-night calls of the birds were all around them. The fragrance of life was around them. It was one of those silences to which come impressions, faiths, longings, not yet born as thoughts. Something in the quality of that silence brought the rescuing sense of its having been good to have lived and done one’s part—that sense which, from places of desolation and over ways rough and steep and dark, can find its way to the meadows of serenity.” Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To show that the pair''s initial sense of anxiety eventually gives way to a profound sense of peacefulness."},{"id":"B","text":"B. To convey the comforting contrast between the quiet pair and the lively sounds of the world surrounding them."},{"id":"C","text":"C. To reveal how the shared silence allows both the old man and the young girl to attain a feeling of contentment."},{"id":"D","text":"D. To explain how the scene’s natural setting inspires a momentary and restorative feeling of satisfaction with life."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is correct because it most accurately describes the main purpose of the text. The text first establishes the sensory environment—the deepening twilight, the sounds of others, the "fragrance of life," and the "silence"—which fosters the emergence of deep, unarticulated feelings ("impressions, faiths, longings"). The second paragraph then explains how the quality of that silence leads to "the rescuing sense of its having been good to have lived and done one''s part." This feeling is described as a transient restoration, capable of finding its way "to the meadows of serenity" even from dark, difficult places. The overall purpose is thus to explain how the particular atmosphere of the scene inspires a brief yet powerful sense of satisfaction with one''s life. Choice A is incorrect because the text gives no suggestion that the pair was experiencing an "initial sense of anxiety"; rather, the text immediately focuses on the evocative power of the silence itself and the feelings it inspires. Choice B is incorrect. Although the text does mention the "laughter of boys and girls" and the "calls of the birds" surrounding the silent pair, the central focus of the text is not on the contrast but on the effect of the silence itself, which is a key element that allows the feeling of serenity to emerge. Choice C is incorrect because, while the text clearly describes the old man and the young girl sitting together, the ultimate feeling of contentment is described generally as "that sense which... can find its way to the meadows of serenity," without specifying that this feeling is uniquely attained by both individuals in the way a shared experience would imply, or that the silence is dependent on the pair being together. The focus is on the power of the silence, not the shared experience of the pair.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A 2014 study led by psychologist Dr. Daniel Gilbert at Harvard University investigated whether people enjoy having time to think more than they expect. Participants were placed alone in an empty room without their phones or books and told to simply sit with their thoughts for several minutes. Many reported afterward that they found the experience unpleasant. In a follow-up experiment, participants were again asked to sit and think, but this time they had access to a device that delivered a mild electric shock. Surprisingly, a significant number of participants chose to shock themselves rather than remain alone with their thoughts. The researchers concluded that many people find internally focused thinking less enjoyable than they anticipate. Which choice best describes the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To show that most people lack the ability to concentrate without external distractions"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To explain a study’s conclusion and the evidence the researchers used to reach that conclusion"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To argue that increased use of technology has made independent thinking more difficult"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To describe a controversial experiment and why it was widely criticized by other scientists"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately describes the main purpose of the text, which is to explain a study’s conclusion and how the researchers arrived at that conclusion. The text begins by summarizing the study’s main finding: many people enjoy spending time alone with their thoughts far less than they expect. It then describes the experiments conducted by Gilbert and his colleagues, including the surprising observation that some participants preferred receiving a mild electric shock to sitting quietly. These experimental results led to the conclusion presented in the opening sentence. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not make a general claim that people lack the ability to concentrate; it focuses on whether people enjoy being alone with their thoughts, not whether they can concentrate. Choice C is incorrect because the passage makes no mention of technology use or its effects on people’s thinking. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not describe the experiment as controversial or discuss any criticism from other scientists; it solely explains the study’s design and conclusion.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from the scientific work of Maria Sibylla Merian, a seventeenth-century naturalist and illustrator. In 1705, Maria Sibylla Merian published Metamorphosis Insectorum Surinamensium, a richly illustrated study of the insects of Suriname. Merian had traveled to the Dutch colony to document its plants and animals firsthand—an unusual undertaking for a European woman at the time. She carefully observed caterpillars, pupae, and adult insects and recorded their life cycles in detailed watercolors. Her book combined these illustrations with written descriptions based on her direct field observations. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To compare European and Surinamese approaches to the study of insects"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To describe a groundbreaking natural history book and how it was produced"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To argue that Merian’s artwork was more influential than her scientific observations"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To explain why scientific expeditions to South America were rare during Merian’s time"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main purpose of the text, which is to describe Merian’s natural history book and how it was created. The passage introduces Metamorphosis Insectorum Surinamensium and then explains Merian’s process—traveling to Suriname, observing insects directly, and combining illustrations with descriptions. Thus, the text focuses primarily on what the book is and how Merian produced it. Choice A is incorrect because although the text mentions Suriname and Merian’s European background, it does not compare European and Surinamese methods of studying insects. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not evaluate whether Merian’s artwork or scientific writing was more influential; it simply notes that both were included in her book. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss the rarity of scientific expeditions or offer reasons why such journeys were uncommon.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1967, folklorist Ralph Rinzler organized the first Smithsonian Folklife Festival on the National Mall in Washington, DC. The event was designed to celebrate living cultural traditions by bringing musicians, craftspeople, and storytellers from across the United States to demonstrate their work directly to the public. The success of the inaugural festival led to its becoming an annual event. Over the decades, the Smithsonian Folklife Festival has expanded to include artists from around the world, continuing its mission of presenting diverse cultural traditions through performance and demonstration. Which choice best describes the overall purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To describe how Rinzler’s early career led him to develop the Smithsonian Folklife Festival"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To argue that the Smithsonian Folklife Festival is the most influential cultural event in Washington, DC"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To explain why the Smithsonian Folklife Festival focuses heavily on international performers today"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To provide an overview of the founding and long-term mission of the Smithsonian Folklife Festival"}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because the text provides a concise history of the Smithsonian Folklife Festival—from its founding in 1967 by Ralph Rinzler, to its expansion into an annual event, to its continued mission of showcasing cultural traditions. The passage’s purpose is to give an overview of both how the festival began and what it aims to do today. Choice A is incorrect. Although the text names Ralph Rinzler, it does not discuss his early career or motivations; it simply states that he organized the first festival. Choice B is incorrect. The text does not claim that the Smithsonian Folklife Festival is the most influential cultural event in Washington, DC, nor does it compare it with other events. Choice C is incorrect. While the passage mentions that the festival expanded to include international performers, it does not explain why this expansion occurred. It treats this as just one moment in the festival’s broader history.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from Robert Frost’s 1920 poem “Fire and Ice.” Some say the world will end in fire, Some say in ice. From what I’ve tasted of desire I hold with those who favor fire. But if it had to perish twice, I think I know enough of hate To say that for destruction ice Is also great And would suffice. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. To express the speaker’s view that powerful human emotions can lead to destruction"},{"id":"B","text":"B. To argue that natural disasters pose the greatest threat to humanity"},{"id":"C","text":"C. To describe past experiences the speaker has had with extreme weather"},{"id":"D","text":"D. To explain why the speaker believes desire is a more admirable feeling than hate"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately reflects the poem’s central purpose: to show that intense human emotions—specifically desire and hate—can be forces destructive enough to “end” or “perish” the world. The speaker aligns fire with desire and ice with hate, suggesting that either emotion, taken to extremes, could bring about ruin. Thus, the poem uses metaphors of fire and ice to convey the destructive power of emotional extremes. Choice B is incorrect because although the poem mentions “fire” and “ice,” they function symbolically, not literally. The text does not focus on natural disasters or argue that they are the greatest threat to humanity. Choice C is incorrect because the speaker’s references to “desire” and “hate” are emotional experiences, not experiences with physical fire or ice. The poem does not describe weather events or personal encounters with them. Choice D is incorrect because while the speaker favors fire (linked with desire) over ice (linked with hate), the poem does not claim that desire is more admirable. Instead, it argues that both emotions can be destructive enough to end the world.', 'craft-structure', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Origami cranes became widely recognized symbols of peace after World War II, but the art form itself has a much older history. Traditional Japanese origami began centuries earlier and was shaped by cultural practices that valued ceremony and precision. As the craft spread during the 19th and early 20th centuries, artists began creating new folding techniques and more complex figures. In the decades that followed, origami continued to evolve as artists experimented with mathematical patterns and innovative design methods. Because of these developments, contemporary origami is far more intricate and varied than the traditional models that preceded it. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To highlight why origami cranes are more meaningful than other symbols."},{"id":"B","text":"To discuss the historical development of an art form."},{"id":"C","text":"To provide instructions for making a traditional paper figure."},{"id":"D","text":"To emphasize the accomplishments of a famous origami artist."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because the text describes how origami began in Japan, how it changed as new techniques developed in the 19th and 20th centuries, and how contemporary origami differs from earlier forms. The passage’s main purpose is to discuss origami’s development over time. Choice A is incorrect. Although the passage mentions that origami cranes became symbols of peace after World War II, it does not argue that cranes are more meaningful than other symbols. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not give folding steps or any instructions for creating origami figures. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not mention any specific artist—famous or otherwise—and does not emphasize individual accomplishments.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from E. Nesbit’s The Railway Children: Peter’s Coal Mine. "What fun!" said Mother, in the dark, feeling for the matches on the table. "How frightened the poor mice were – I don’t believe they were rats at all." She struck a match and relighted the candle and everyone looked at each other by its winky, blinky light. "Well," she said, "you’ve often wanted something to happen and now it has. This is quite an adventure, isn’t it? I told Mrs. Viney to get us some bread and butter, and meat and things, and to have supper ready. I suppose she’s laid it in the dining room. So let’s go and see." Which choice best describes the overall purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To show how nervous the children were about the dark."},{"id":"B","text":"To illustrate how Mother encourages the family to enjoy a small adventure."},{"id":"C","text":"To describe Mrs. Viney’s preparations for supper."},{"id":"D","text":"To explain why Mother dislikes mice in the house."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately describes the overall purpose of the text. The passage shows Mother reacting to a surprising situation in the dark and framing it as a fun experience for the family, saying, "This is quite an adventure, isn’t it?" She then prepares everyone to enjoy the moment together. Thus, the overall purpose is to illustrate how Mother encourages the family to enjoy a small adventure. Choice A is incorrect because the passage mentions that the mice were frightened, not the children. Choice C is incorrect because Mrs. Viney’s preparations for supper are mentioned briefly as a detail and are not the main purpose. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not suggest that Mother dislikes mice; she comments on their fright rather than expressing annoyance or fear.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from O. Henry’s The Gift of the Magi. One dollar and eighty-seven cents. That was all. And sixty cents of it was in pennies. Pennies saved one and two at a time by bulldozing the grocer and the vegetable man and the butcher until one’s cheeks burned with the silent imputation of parsimony that such close dealing implied. Three times Della counted it. One dollar and eighty-seven cents. And the next day would be Christmas. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To describe how Della carefully saved money and how little she has to spend for Christmas"},{"id":"B","text":"To argue that people should save money for holidays instead of spending it freely"},{"id":"C","text":"To explain why Della dislikes shopping at the grocer, vegetable man, and butcher"},{"id":"D","text":"To compare Della’s Christmas spending with that of other characters"}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately states the main purpose of the text. The passage focuses on Della counting her money—only “one dollar and eighty-seven cents”—and highlights the effort she took to save pennies over time, especially in preparation for Christmas. The main purpose is to show both how carefully Della saved and how limited her funds are for the holiday. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not give advice or argue that others should save money; it only describes Della’s actions. Choice C is incorrect because while Della deals with merchants, the text emphasizes her careful saving, not dislike of shopping. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not mention any other characters’ spending or make comparisons; the focus is solely on Della.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Oscar Wilde’s The Happy Prince. High above the city, on a tall column, stood the statue of the Happy Prince. He was gilded all over with thin leaves of fine gold, for eyes he had two bright sapphires, and a large red ruby glowed on his sword-hilt. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To explain why the Happy Prince was placed on a tall column"},{"id":"B","text":"To describe the appearance of the statue of the Happy Prince"},{"id":"C","text":"To compare the Happy Prince to other statues in the city"},{"id":"D","text":"To suggest that the Happy Prince was unhappy despite his wealth"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main purpose of the text. The passage focuses on the physical characteristics of the statue, describing the gold gilding, sapphire eyes, and the ruby on the sword-hilt. The overall purpose is to convey a clear image of how the Happy Prince statue looks to the reader. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not explain why the statue was placed on a column; it only mentions that it stands on one. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not compare this statue to any other statues in the city. Choice D is incorrect because the text focuses entirely on the statue’s outward appearance and does not indicate the Prince’s feelings or emotions.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Rabindranath Tagore’s The Kabuliwala. My five-year-old daughter Mini cannot live without chattering. I really believe that in all her life she has not wasted a minute in silence. Her mother is often vexed at this, and would stop her prattle, but I would not. To see Mini quiet is unnatural, and I cannot bear it long. And so my own talk with her is always lively. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To show how Mini’s mother tries to limit her talking"},{"id":"B","text":"To explain why Mini’s father enjoys talking with her"},{"id":"C","text":"To describe Mini’s daily routine"},{"id":"D","text":"To illustrate why Mini struggles in school"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main purpose of the text. The passage emphasizes that the narrator enjoys Mini’s constant talking and lively conversation, even when his wife finds it vexing. The overall focus is on the father’s enjoyment of interacting with his daughter. Choice A is incorrect because although the text mentions Mini’s mother trying to stop her talking, that is not the main focus of the passage. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not provide details about Mini’s daily routine; it focuses on her chattering and her father’s reaction. Choice D is incorrect because there is no mention of school or learning difficulties in the text.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is from William Blake’s 1794 poem “The Sick Rose.” O Rose, thou art sick. The invisible worm, That flies in the night In the howling storm: Has found out thy bed Of crimson joy: And his dark secret love Does thy life destroy. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To show that roses are easily damaged by pests"},{"id":"B","text":"To warn about the destructive power of hidden forces"},{"id":"C","text":"To describe the life cycle of a rose"},{"id":"D","text":"To celebrate the beauty of roses"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately states the text’s main purpose. The poem presents the rose as “sick” and describes an “invisible worm” that attacks it, using imagery of secrecy and destruction (“his dark secret love / Does thy life destroy”). These lines suggest that unseen or hidden forces can have a harmful effect. Thus, the main purpose is to warn about the destructive power of hidden forces. Choice A is incorrect because the poem uses the worm symbolically; it is not literally about pests damaging roses. Choice C is incorrect because the poem does not describe the natural life cycle of a rose, but rather focuses on harm caused by a hidden agent. Choice D is incorrect because, while the rose is mentioned, the poem emphasizes damage and destruction, not celebration of beauty.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'New York State implemented a law on March 1, 2020, that bans most single-use plastic carryout bags. The measure took effect in stores statewide, with exceptions for certain types of bags. Enforcement began on October 19, 2020, following a court decision. At the same time, local governments are allowed to impose a five-cent fee on paper bags to encourage use of reusable alternatives. According to New York City’s 2023 Waste Characterization Study, plastic shopping bags in the trash stream dropped by 68% between 2017 and 2023. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To argue that the plastic bag ban has been too weak because paper bags are still being used"},{"id":"B","text":"To describe New York State’s law on plastic bags and its initial environmental impact"},{"id":"C","text":"To explain how New York collects fees from retailers for plastic bag distribution"},{"id":"D","text":"To compare New York’s ban on plastic bags to similar bans in other states"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the passage explains the specifics of New York’s plastic bag ban, the timing of its enforcement, the option for local paper-bag fees, and data showing a substantial decline in plastic bag waste. These details align precisely with the purpose of describing the law and its early impact. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not argue that the law is weak—it reports on the policy and its effects rather than making a critique. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not mention how New York collects revenue from retailers for bags—it talks about a fee on paper bags charged to consumers, not retailers. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not compare New York’s policy with those of other states; it focuses solely on New York.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Hip-hop dance first developed in African American and Latino communities in New York City during the 1970s. Early hip-hop dancers were influenced by funk, soul, and disco music, and they often performed on street corners, at block parties, or in local community centers. Over time, hip-hop dance evolved to include a wide range of styles, such as breaking, popping, and locking. By the 1980s and 1990s, hip-hop dance had become a popular and influential art form that shaped music videos, television shows, and global youth culture. Which choice best states the main purpose of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"To explain why hip-hop music is more popular than other music genres"},{"id":"B","text":"To discuss the development of hip-hop dance"},{"id":"C","text":"To describe the rules and techniques of breaking"},{"id":"D","text":"To highlight famous hip-hop dancers from New York City"}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the passage focuses on the origins of hip-hop dance, the musical and cultural influences that shaped it, and how it evolved into a globally influential dance form. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not discuss the popularity of hip-hop music relative to other genres. Choice C is incorrect because the passage mentions breaking as one style of hip-hop dance but does not explain its rules or techniques. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not focus on individual dancers; it focuses on the broader development of hip-hop dance.', 'craft-structure', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Thomas Hardy’s 1874 novel Far from the Madding Crowd: Bathsheba stood motionless at the threshold, the unopened letter still in her hand. A strange foreboding had seized her—an uneasy sense that whatever lay within those pages would alter the quiet course of her thoughts. Yet she hesitated to break the seal. The evening light fell across the farmyard, but she felt curiously apart from it, as though suspended in a moment that asked something of her she was not prepared to give. What is the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Bathsheba anxiously postpones reading a letter because she senses it may bring significant emotional consequences."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Bathsheba eagerly anticipates good news in a letter but restrains herself out of politeness."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Bathsheba avoids opening a letter because she is distracted by more urgent responsibilities on the farm."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Bathsheba ignores an ordinary letter, believing it to be unimportant to her immediate concerns."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately captures the central idea of the passage. The text emphasizes Bathsheba’s hesitation and apprehension: she feels a “strange foreboding” and an “uneasy sense” that the letter may “alter the quiet course of her thoughts.” Her decision to delay opening it shows that she anticipates the letter will have significant emotional impact. Thus, the main idea is that Bathsheba is anxious about the contents of the letter and postpones reading it. Choice B is incorrect because the passage never suggests that Bathsheba is looking forward to good news; instead, she feels dread rather than excitement. Choice C is incorrect because Bathsheba is not distracted by farm responsibilities—the text specifically notes that she feels “apart” from her surroundings, not drawn to other tasks. Choice D is incorrect because the letter is clearly not ordinary or unimportant to her; the entire passage stresses its weight and her emotional response to it.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Mary Shelley’s 1818 novel Frankenstein: The weather was fine, and the sky cloudless; but the air was cold, and the ground covered with snow. As the light wind blew from the peaks of the mountains, I felt refreshed in its presence, though my spirits were depressed by the consequences of my late actions. I passed several hours upon the ice, contemplating the magnificent scenery around me, and the stillness seemed a natural response to the turmoil of my thoughts. At length, recollecting myself, I proceeded toward the village with slow and thoughtful steps. What is the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The narrator lingers in a snowy landscape, finding that its quiet majesty mirrors his troubled inner state."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The narrator becomes lost on an icy mountain path and fears he will be unable to reach the village."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The narrator is cheered by the beautiful weather and walks quickly toward the village in high spirits."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Surprised by the sudden cold and heavy snowfall, the narrator seeks shelter immediately in the nearest village."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately captures the core idea of the passage. The narrator observes the “magnificent scenery,” feels “refreshed,” but is also burdened by emotional turmoil resulting from his recent actions. His slow, reflective walk and the stillness of the icy environment parallel his troubled thoughts, making option A the most precise summary. Choice B is incorrect because although the narrator is on ice and snow, the passage never states that he becomes lost or fears being unable to reach the village. Choice C is incorrect because, while the weather is fine, the narrator is not cheerful—his “spirits were depressed,” contradicting the idea of high spirits or quick movement. Choice D is incorrect because the narrator is not surprised by the cold, nor does he seek immediate shelter; he spends “several hours” contemplating the scenery before returning to the village.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from John Steinbeck’s 1952 novel East of Eden: When a child first catches adults out—when it first walks into his grave little head that adults do not always have divine intelligence, that their judgments are not always wise, their thinking true, their sentences just—his world falls into panic and desolation. The gods are fallen and all safety gone. And there is one sure thing about the fall of gods: they do not fall a little; they crash and shatter or sink deeply into green muck. It is a tedious job to build them up again; they never quite shine. And the child’s world is never quite whole again. It is an aching kind of growing. What is the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. A child’s discovery that adults are flawed brings a painful but formative shift in the child’s understanding of the world."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Childhood innocence is lost only when adults display extreme moral corruption in front of a child."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Although adults occasionally make mistakes, children recover quickly and rebuild their trust in them."},{"id":"D","text":"D. A child naturally distrusts adults, and this distrust gradually intensifies as the child matures."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately captures the main idea of the passage. The text describes the moment a child realizes that adults are not infallible—“the gods are fallen and all safety gone”—and emphasizes how painful and disorienting this discovery is. It also explains that rebuilding trust is difficult and incomplete, noting that the “gods…never quite shine” again. This clearly supports the idea that the child undergoes a painful but important shift in understanding, which aligns with option A. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not suggest that adults must commit extreme moral wrongdoing for the child to lose innocence; instead, even the simple awareness of adult imperfection is enough. Choice C is incorrect because the text explicitly states that rebuilding the image of adults is “tedious” and incomplete, contradicting the idea that children recover quickly. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not claim that children naturally begin with distrust. On the contrary, it shows that the child initially sees adults as godlike and only later experiences disillusionment.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Architect and environmental psychologist Thomas A. Heinz has long argued that exposure to unusual spatial geometry can sharpen attention and improve mental flexibility. One experimental house he documented—originally designed by R. Buckminster Fuller—features slanted interior walls, uneven floor gradients, and windows placed at unconventional heights. The layout initially disorients visitors, but longtime resident Claire Parker reported that after several years in the home, she experienced improved concentration and heightened spatial awareness. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Fuller’s experimental house became popular because many people wanted to experience its unconventional geometry."},{"id":"B","text":"Heinz’s work suggests that living in an intentionally disorienting environment may offer cognitive benefits despite practical challenges."},{"id":"C","text":"Although Parker admired Fuller’s architectural vision, she found it too impractical for long-term habitation."},{"id":"D","text":"Fuller’s architectural experiments were more influential in psychology than in architecture."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately reflects the main idea of the text. The passage explains that architect and psychologist Thomas A. Heinz believes exposure to unusual spatial geometry can sharpen mental functioning. It then describes a Fuller-designed experimental house with disorienting features such as slanted walls and uneven floors. Importantly, longtime resident Claire Parker reported cognitive improvements after living in it for several years. These details support the idea that such impractical yet deliberately disorienting environments may yield benefits. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not mention widespread popularity or public interest in experiencing the house. It focuses on Heinz’s claims and Parker’s personal experience rather than broader public reactions. Choice C is incorrect because nothing in the text suggests that Parker found the house unsuitable or impractical to live in; instead, she reports positive cognitive outcomes. While the design is unusual, the text does not imply Parker objected to it. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not compare Fuller’s influence across different fields. Fuller is mentioned only as the designer of the experimental house, not as a figure whose broader influence is evaluated.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from the American author Donna Tartt’s debut novel “The Secret History.” “It’s a very Greek idea, and a very profound one. Beauty is terror. Whatever we call beautiful, we quiver before it. And what could be more terrifying and beautiful, to souls like the Greeks or our own, than to lose control completely? To throw off the chains of being for an instant, to shatter the accident of our mortal selves? Euripides speaks of the Maenads: head thrown back, throat to the stars, ‘more like deer than human being.’ To be absolutely free! One is quite capable, of course, of working out these destructive passions in more vulgar and less efficient ways. But how glorious to release them in a single burst! To sing, to scream, to dance barefoot in the woods in the dead of night, with no more awareness of mortality than an animal! These are powerful mysteries. The bellowing of bulls. Springs of honey bubbling from the ground. If we are strong enough in our souls we can rip away the veil and look that naked, terrible beauty right in the face; let God consume us, devour us, unstring our bones. Then spit us out reborn.” What is the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The speaker argues that ancient Greek rituals were dangerous and should not be repeated in the modern world."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The speaker suggests that true beauty evokes both fear and awe, and that losing oneself in moments of ecstatic freedom can be transformative."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The speaker claims that ordinary life provides enough opportunities for self-expression, making extreme emotional experiences unnecessary."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The speaker believes that the Maenads in Euripides’ work were historical figures whose behavior should be imitated for spiritual growth."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is correct because the passage emphasizes that beauty is intertwined with terror and that moments of ecstatic self-abandonment—symbolized through Greek myth and ritual—offer a way to experience powerful, transformative freedom. The speaker repeatedly describes such moments as profound, terrifying, and capable of metaphorically “rebirth.” Choice A is incorrect because the speaker does not condemn Greek rituals or warn against reenacting them; instead, the tone is admiring and fascinated. Choice C is incorrect because the passage explicitly argues the opposite—that everyday outlets for passion are “vulgar” or insufficient, and that extreme ecstatic experiences are “glorious.” Choice D is incorrect because the speaker refers to Euripides’ Maenads in a literary and symbolic sense, not as people whose behavior should literally be imitated.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Charlotte Perkins Gilman’s (1892) short story “The Yellow Wallpaper.” I lie here on this great immovable bed—it is nailed down, I believe—and follow that pattern about by the hour. It is as though the walls themselves form a kind of crawling, confusing figure that I cannot quite disentangle. John, my husband, says I am gaining slowly, but his voice frightens me sometimes. He does not understand how much the wallpaper bothers me. He thinks rest and confinement are best for my “nerves,” so he watches me with a calm, scientific air. He brings me food, and he says I must not write, but his manner never changes, always rational, always in control. And yet, I feel that I exist behind that wallpaper, trapped in its design—part of it, even—while I remain ignored in every other way. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The narrator resents her husband for confining her to a room she dislikes."},{"id":"B","text":"The narrator feels deeply disturbed by the wallpaper and isolated from her husband’s understanding."},{"id":"C","text":"The narrator wants to convince her husband to allow her to write more."},{"id":"D","text":"The narrator believes that removing the wallpaper will restore her mental health."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately captures the main idea of the passage. The text describes how the narrator is haunted by the wallpaper’s pattern (“crawling, confusing figure”) and feels that her husband does not truly understand her distress, treating her with rational detachment. Her sense of isolation and her psychological disturbance are central. Choice A is incorrect because, while she does feel confined, the passage does not emphasize resentment toward her husband—rather, it emphasizes her misunderstood suffering. Choice C is incorrect because the narrator mentions that her husband forbids her writing, but she doesn’t directly express a demand to persuade him to change that policy; the passage focuses more on her emotional state than on a plea. Choice D is incorrect because the narrator does not say outright that removing the wallpaper would cure her; she feels trapped in it, but she does not explicitly connect its removal to recovery in this excerpt.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Many art historians differentiate between form, the compositional architecture of an artwork, and content, the thematic or representational material it conveys. In Pablo Picasso’s Guernica, the formal schema comprises fractured geometries and jagged planes, whereas the content manifests the anguish and turmoil engendered by war. Yet art theorist Rosalind Krauss contended that an exclusive focus on form and content is inadequate for apprehending the full semantic richness of a work. She argued that rigid taxonomies often occlude the nuanced processes through which meaning is generated via the dialectical interplay among the artist, the artifact, and its audience. Which choice best encapsulates the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Rosalind Krauss posited that conventional analytical binaries, such as form and content, fail to encompass crucial dimensions of meaning that emerge through the interaction of the artist, the artwork, and the audience."},{"id":"B","text":"Rosalind Krauss asserted that the significance of an artwork resides entirely in the subjective perception of the observer, independent of the artist’s intentions or the intrinsic properties of the work."},{"id":"C","text":"Although Picasso’s Guernica employs complex formal strategies, its meaning can be exhaustively discerned by analyzing its form and content."},{"id":"D","text":"Artworks composed of abstract or fragmented forms are intrinsically less intelligible to viewers than artworks with representational or realistic forms."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most precisely articulates the main argument. The passage first delineates the prevalent analytical distinction between form (structure) and content (subject matter), exemplified by Picasso’s Guernica. It then introduces Krauss’s critique, emphasizing that exclusive reliance on such dichotomies obscures the multifaceted mechanisms through which meaning emerges from the interactions among artist, work, and audience. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not claim that meaning exists solely in the observer’s perception; it emphasizes the triadic interaction among artist, work, and audience. Choice C is incorrect because the passage explicitly notes that form and content alone are insufficient to apprehend a work’s full semantic depth. Choice D is incorrect because the discussion of abstract or fragmented forms serves only to illustrate broader theoretical points, not to assert their inherent difficulty for comprehension.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Madagascar is one of the world’s most ecologically unique places due to its long isolation. Nearly eighty percent of its species exist nowhere else on Earth, earning the island the nickname “the Eighth Continent.” Its distinctive wildlife includes lemurs and fossas, and its flora features the thick-trunked baobab trees. However, Madagascar faces severe economic challenges, with roughly three-quarters of its population living in extreme poverty. Desperation has led many locals to engage in slash-and-burn agriculture, threatening the island’s natural ecosystems. The Makira Project, a collaboration between Madagascar''s Ministry of the Environment and Forests and the Wildlife Conservation Society, works to preserve 372,000 hectares in Makira Natural Park. The project also seeks to improve economic conditions for local communities, thereby reducing the need to deforest the area. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"The Makira Project demonstrates the value of partnerships between government agencies and conservation organizations."},{"id":"B","text":"Conservation initiatives that address both environmental preservation and local economic needs can effectively protect ecosystems."},{"id":"C","text":"Madagascar’s wildlife, including lemurs and baobab trees, is threatened by slash-and-burn agriculture."},{"id":"D","text":"Economically impoverished populations are the primary cause of ecological destruction on Madagascar."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately conveys the main idea of the passage. The text emphasizes that the Makira Project is successful not only in protecting a large portion of Madagascar’s unique ecosystems but also in improving the economic well-being of local communities, thereby reducing destructive human practices. In other words, integrating environmental and economic goals can make conservation initiatives more effective. Choice A is incorrect because while the passage highlights the collaboration between governmental and non-governmental organizations, this partnership serves to illustrate a broader point rather than being the central idea. Choice C is incorrect because the text mentions threats to wildlife primarily as background information to contextualize the project; it is not the main argument. Choice D is incorrect because although poverty contributes to environmental degradation, the passage focuses on how targeted conservation strategies can address both ecological and socioeconomic challenges, rather than solely blaming local populations.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Seventeenth-century astronomer Johannes Kepler is widely celebrated for his laws of planetary motion, which describe how planets orbit the sun. However, as historian Owen Gingerich notes, Kepler originally formulated these laws within the context of astrology and a belief in a cosmic harmony designed by God. His writings linking planetary motion to mystical and numerological principles were largely ignored for decades. It was only in the twentieth century that astronomers and historians of science selectively emphasized Kepler’s laws as precise mathematical models of planetary dynamics, often downplaying or disregarding the theological and mystical motivations that informed his original work. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Although Kepler is famous for his laws of planetary motion, the laws were only widely appreciated in the twentieth century when astronomers reframed them as precise mathematical models."},{"id":"B","text":"Some twentieth-century scientists and historians interpreted Kepler’s laws of planetary motion as purely mathematical models, even though they were originally developed within a mystical and theological framework."},{"id":"C","text":"Kepler’s laws of planetary motion were originally intended to demonstrate the divine harmony of the cosmos, but they also accurately describe planetary orbits."},{"id":"D","text":"Kepler’s early work on astrology and cosmic numerology made his contributions to astronomy confusing and difficult for later scientists to understand."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately reflects the main idea of the text. The passage explains that although Kepler formulated his laws of planetary motion, he did so within a theological and mystical framework, and these aspects were largely ignored. In the twentieth century, scientists and historians emphasized the laws’ mathematical precision while downplaying the original mystical context. Thus, the central point is that the later interpretation of Kepler’s work selectively reframed it, separating it from its original intentions. Choice A is incorrect because, while it notes the twentieth-century reframing, it does not emphasize that the reinterpretation disregarded the mystical and theological context that originally informed Kepler’s work. Choice C is incorrect because although the passage mentions that Kepler’s laws were developed with theological motivations, the text emphasizes the selective reinterpretation by later scientists, not the laws’ original accuracy. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not claim that Kepler’s work was confusing or difficult for later scientists; rather, the focus is on how later interpreters reframed the laws to fit modern scientific paradigms.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Fyodor Dostoevsky’s The Brothers Karamazov. In it, the narrator reflects on his contradictory feelings toward humanity. “The more I love humanity in general the less I love man in particular. In my dreams, I often make plans for the service of humanity, and perhaps I might actually face crucifixion if it were suddenly necessary. Yet I am incapable of living in the same room with anyone for two days together. I know from experience. As soon as anyone is near me, his personality disturbs me and restricts my freedom. In twenty-four hours I begin to hate the best of men: one because he’s too long over his dinner, another because he has a cold and keeps on blowing his nose. I become hostile to people the moment they come close to me. But it has always happened that the more I hate men individually the more I love humanity.” What is the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The narrator dreams of serving humanity, yet he admits that people’s minor flaws make him despise them and renounce all charitable ideals."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The narrator regrets his inability to love individuals and wishes he could overcome his failings so that he might truly serve others."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The narrator experiences a profound contradiction: though he imagines himself capable of heroic sacrifice for humanity, he cannot tolerate the presence of individual people and grows hostile toward them."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The narrator believes that humanity has become too corrupt to deserve compassion and that solitude is the only means of preserving one’s dignity."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately captures the central contradiction that drives the passage. At the beginning of the text, the narrator asserts that he loves “humanity in general” so deeply that he might even “face crucifixion” for its sake. However, the passage immediately explains that when individuals come near him, he becomes irritated by even the smallest habits—someone eating too slowly or blowing his nose—and quickly begins to “hate the best of men.” Overall, the primary purpose of the text is to emphasize the narrator’s paradoxical belief that he can adore humanity as an abstract ideal while being hostile toward actual human beings. Choice A is incorrect because, although the narrator dislikes the trivial habits of real individuals, he does not renounce or abandon his grand plans for serving humanity; he continues to affirm his ability to sacrifice himself for it. Choice B is incorrect because the narrator never expresses regret or a desire to change his behavior. Rather than lamenting his failings, he reports them as a fact. Choice D is incorrect because the narrator does not argue that people are corrupt or undeserving of compassion. Instead, he claims that his own personality becomes hostile simply when people are near him.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Narrative theory often distinguishes between the temporal sequence in which events occur and the order in which those events are disclosed to an audience. In narratives that adhere to a strictly chronological structure, these two sequences coincide, creating the impression that the story simply unfolds as it happened. However, scholars of narrative form caution against treating such alignment as narratively neutral. They argue that even when a narrative preserves chronological order, the decision to withhold, condense, or foreground certain events shapes interpretation. More overt departures from chronology—such as flashbacks or parallel timelines—make this shaping function explicit, revealing that narrative meaning arises not from temporal sequence alone but from the deliberate organization of information across time. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Narrative scholars contend that both chronological and non-chronological storytelling demonstrate that meaning in narratives depends on how information is organized, not merely on the order in which events occur."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Chronological narratives give audiences the false impression that stories present events objectively, even though all narratives involve selective emphasis."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Non-chronological narrative techniques expose the artificiality of storytelling by drawing attention to the gap between events and their representation."},{"id":"D","text":"D. C. Non-chronological narrative techniques expose the artificiality of storytelling by drawing attention to the gap between events and their representation."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it synthesizes the entire passage: the initial distinction, the critique of chronological neutrality, and the concluding claim that narrative meaning depends on organizational choices rather than temporal sequence alone. Choice B is incorrect because although the passage suggests that chronological narratives appear neutral, it does not focus on audience deception or objectivity as its central claim; this choice narrows one implication into an overstated main idea. Choice C is incorrect because while the passage discusses how non-chronological techniques make narrative shaping visible, it does not argue that their purpose is to expose storytelling as artificial; that interpretation goes beyond the text. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not compare the effectiveness of chronological versus non-chronological storytelling; it treats both as evidence for a broader theoretical point rather than ranking one as superior.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Convinced that traditional classroom layouts encourage passivity, education researcher Helena Ortiz redesigned a public high school’s learning spaces to resist comfort and predictability. Chairs varied in height and stability, desks were arranged irregularly rather than in rows, and corridors narrowed unexpectedly. Although students initially found the environment distracting, a longitudinal study conducted over three years found measurable gains in student alertness and sustained attention, suggesting that the school’s unconventional design may have contributed to improved cognitive engagement. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Although initially disruptive, an unconventional school design implemented by Ortiz may enhance students’ cognitive engagement."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Irregular classroom furniture is more effective than traditional teaching methods at improving student attention."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Education researcher Helena Ortiz has consistently opposed traditional classroom layouts throughout her career."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Students learn best when educational spaces are designed to be uncomfortable and unpredictable."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The text describes how education researcher Helena Ortiz redesigned a school learning environment to be intentionally unconventional and initially distracting. It then explains that, despite students’ early discomfort, a long-term study found improvements in alertness and sustained attention. Thus, the main idea is that although the design was impractical and disruptive at first, it may have had positive effects on students’ cognitive engagement. Choice B is incorrect because the text does not compare classroom design to teaching methods or claim that irregular furniture is more effective than traditional instruction; it discusses only the potential benefits of a specific environmental redesign. Choice C is incorrect because while the text identifies Ortiz as the designer of the school, it does not provide information about her broader career or suggest that she has consistently opposed traditional classroom layouts. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not argue that students learn best in uncomfortable or unpredictable spaces; it presents a single case study and reports possible benefits without making a universal claim.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Although John James Audubon had encountered Alexander Wilson’s American Ornithology as early as 1810, he did not immediately pursue a comparable project of his own. A decade later, however, Audubon resolved to publish his own bird illustrations and began collecting and drawing with that goal in mind. Traveling with Joseph Mason, an artist skilled in rendering plants and insects, Audubon expanded his work across the Mississippi River region. During this period, he also shifted his artistic techniques, receiving limited formal instruction in oil painting and increasingly favoring watercolors. When Audubon attempted to gain institutional support in Philadelphia in 1824, his efforts were unsuccessful, partly because his project was perceived as a challenge to the already established work of Wilson. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Audubon’s artistic development was shaped by his extensive travels and his collaboration with Joseph Mason, leading to major changes in his preferred artistic media."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Although Audubon had early exposure to Wilson’s work, his pursuit of publishing bird illustrations developed later and faced resistance due to competition with Wilson."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Audubon failed to secure sponsorship in Philadelphia because he lacked sufficient formal training in oil painting and watercolor techniques."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Wilson’s American Ornithology dominated early nineteenth-century bird illustration to such an extent that later artists struggled to gain recognition."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that although Audubon was familiar with Alexander Wilson’s work early on, he only later decided to publish his own bird illustrations. It then describes Audubon’s efforts to develop this project and notes that he encountered resistance when seeking sponsorship, largely because his work was seen as competing with Wilson’s. Thus, the main idea centers on the delayed emergence of Audubon’s project and the challenges he faced due to Wilson’s established reputation. Choice A is incorrect because, while the text mentions Audubon’s travels and changes in artistic media, these details serve as background rather than the central focus of the passage. Choice C is incorrect because the text does not state that Audubon’s lack of formal training caused his failure to secure sponsorship; instead, it attributes this outcome to perceptions of his demeanor and competition with Wilson. Choice D is incorrect because although Wilson’s prominence is referenced, the passage does not broadly discuss the state of nineteenth-century bird illustration or suggest that later artists generally struggled for recognition.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Edgar Allan Poe’s 1843 short story “The Tell-Tale Heart.” TRUE!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am! But why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how calmly—how healthily—I can tell you the whole story. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The narrator insists that heightened sensory perception proves mental clarity rather than madness."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The narrator insists that heightened sensory perception proves mental clarity rather than madness."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The narrator explains the supernatural experiences that led others to believe he was mad."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The narrator calmly recounts past events to demonstrate control over his emotions."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The narrator repeatedly denies being mad and argues instead that his condition has sharpened his senses, particularly his hearing. He presents this heightened perception as evidence of mental clarity and rationality, making his insistence on sanity the central focus of the passage. Choice B is incorrect because although the narrator mentions a “disease” and altered hearing, the passage does not focus on explaining a medical condition; these details are used to support his claim of sanity, not to describe an illness. Choice C is incorrect because while the narrator alludes to hearing extraordinary things, the passage does not explain supernatural experiences or suggest that they caused others to label him mad. Choice D is incorrect because although the narrator claims to speak calmly, the passage does not involve recounting specific past events or demonstrating emotional control beyond asserting mental soundness.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1916, Albert Einstein predicted the existence of gravitational waves—ripples in spacetime produced by accelerating massive objects—but for decades these waves remained undetected. That changed in 2015, when researchers working with the Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory (LIGO) announced that they had recorded a signal generated by the merger of two black holes over a billion light-years away. By measuring minute distortions in spacetime using laser interferometry, the team provided the first direct observational evidence of gravitational waves, confirming a key prediction of general relativity. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Scientists have obtained direct observational evidence confirming the existence of gravitational waves predicted by Einstein."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Laser interferometry is the most precise method available for measuring extremely small changes in spacetime."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The merger of two distant black holes produced a detectable signal that reshaped modern astrophysical theory."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Einstein’s theory of general relativity remained controversial until advanced technology became available."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that although gravitational waves were predicted by Einstein in 1916, they were not directly detected until 2015, when LIGO researchers successfully recorded a signal caused by merging black holes. Thus, the central point of the text is that scientists finally obtained direct evidence confirming the existence of gravitational waves. Choice B is incorrect because although laser interferometry is mentioned as part of the detection process, the text does not focus on evaluating or promoting this method in general. Choice C is incorrect because the black hole merger is discussed only as the source of the signal, not as the primary subject of the passage or as something that “reshaped” theory. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not state that general relativity was controversial or disputed; instead, it emphasizes that one of its predictions lacked direct observational confirmation until recently.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The Smithsonian Institution’s National Museum of Asian Art houses an extensive collection ranging from ancient sculptures to modern paintings. In addition to displaying these works, the museum offers public workshops in which visitors can learn traditional artistic techniques, such as brush painting and ceramic glazing, before creating their own pieces inspired by objects in the collection. These programs are designed to deepen visitors’ engagement by allowing them to actively participate in artistic practices rather than only observing finished works. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The National Museum of Asian Art focuses primarily on preserving ancient artworks rather than showcasing modern ones."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The museum allows visitors to both view artworks and actively engage in creating art through hands-on programs."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Public workshops at museums are intended mainly to teach technical skills in traditional art forms."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The Smithsonian Institution uses visitor-created artwork to expand its permanent collection."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that the National Museum of Asian Art not only displays a wide range of artworks but also offers workshops that allow visitors to participate directly in artistic creation. Thus, the central focus is on combining observation of art with active engagement through hands-on programs. Choice A is incorrect because although ancient artworks are mentioned, the text also references modern works and does not claim that preservation of ancient art is the museum’s primary focus. Choice C is incorrect because while workshops teach artistic techniques, the text emphasizes visitor engagement rather than skill instruction as the main purpose. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not state or imply that visitor-created artwork becomes part of the museum’s permanent collection.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'For centuries, Polynesian wayfinders have navigated vast ocean distances using detailed knowledge of stars, ocean swells, winds, and wildlife. These navigators also passed this knowledge orally to successive generations, ensuring the survival of non-instrument navigation traditions. Although modern navigation technologies such as GPS are now widely used, Polynesian wayfinding continues to be taught and practiced, particularly through cultural revival efforts that emphasize preserving ancestral knowledge and identity. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Despite the widespread use of modern navigation technology, Polynesian wayfinding remains valued for preserving traditional knowledge."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Polynesian wayfinders relied entirely on memorization rather than tools to navigate across the Pacific Ocean."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Modern navigation technologies have largely replaced the need for traditional Polynesian navigation practices."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Cultural revival efforts focus more on historical research than on teaching navigation skills."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that Polynesian wayfinders traditionally navigated using environmental knowledge passed down orally and notes that although modern technologies are now common, these navigation practices continue to be taught and valued as part of cultural preservation efforts. Choice B is incorrect because although the text mentions oral transmission of knowledge, it does not claim that wayfinders relied entirely on memorization or exclude the use of environmental cues. Choice C is incorrect because the passage explicitly states that traditional wayfinding continues to be practiced despite modern technology, not that it has been replaced. Choice D is incorrect because while cultural revival efforts are mentioned, the text does not suggest that these efforts prioritize historical research over the active teaching of navigation skills.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'To produce her large-scale ceramic installations, Japanese artist Yayoi Kusama often works with industrial materials rather than traditional clay alone. For several of her outdoor sculptures, she has collaborated with manufacturing facilities to mold fiberglass-reinforced plastic, which allows the works to withstand weather exposure while maintaining precise surface patterns. Kusama then applies her signature polka-dot designs using durable industrial paints, adapting her artistic process to suit the physical demands of public display. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Kusama prefers industrial materials because they are less expensive than traditional ceramic media."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Kusama adapts her artistic process by using industrial materials and techniques to create durable large-scale works."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Polka dots are the defining feature of Kusama’s outdoor sculptures."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Manufacturing facilities play a more important role than artists in the creation of public sculptures."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. It best states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that Kusama uses industrial materials and collaborates with manufacturing facilities to produce large-scale sculptures that can endure outdoor conditions, and it describes how she adjusts her techniques accordingly. Choice A is incorrect. The text does not discuss cost or suggest that Kusama chooses industrial materials because they are cheaper. Choice C is incorrect. Although polka dots are mentioned, they are presented as a detail rather than the central focus of the passage. Choice D is incorrect. The text does not claim that manufacturing facilities are more important than the artist; it describes collaboration, not a shift in creative control.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'At nearly eight hundred pages, The Great Influenza, written by historian John M. Barry, presents an ambitious account of the 1918 influenza pandemic and its impact on public health, politics, and scientific research in the United States. Barry draws on government records, medical journals, and personal correspondence to document both the spread of the disease and the development of modern epidemiology. While the book is widely regarded as a definitive narrative of the pandemic, its emphasis on institutional decision-making sometimes comes at the expense of sustained attention to the everyday experiences of ordinary citizens. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The Great Influenza provides an inaccurate portrayal of the 1918 pandemic because it relies too heavily on official government records."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The length of The Great Influenza makes it difficult for readers without a background in epidemiology to understand."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The Great Influenza primarily examines the personal stories of individuals affected by the 1918 influenza pandemic."},{"id":"D","text":"D. John M. Barry’s The Great Influenza offers a thorough and influential account of the 1918 pandemic, though its focus has a notable limitation."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage describes The Great Influenza as an ambitious and well-regarded work that draws on extensive sources to document the 1918 pandemic and its broader significance. However, it also notes a limitation in the book’s approach: its focus on institutions and decision-making reduces attention to ordinary people’s experiences. Thus, the main idea is that the book is a valuable and comprehensive account with an important shortcoming. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not suggest that the book is inaccurate or that its reliance on government records undermines its credibility. In fact, the passage presents the use of such sources as part of the book’s strength. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not discuss the book’s accessibility to readers or claim that its length makes it difficult to understand. The criticism is about emphasis and perspective, not readability. Choice C is incorrect because the text explicitly states the opposite: it notes that the book does not focus extensively on the everyday experiences of ordinary citizens.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In an urbanised estuary in Australia, marine ecologist M. Mayer-Pinto and colleagues examined how artificial coastal structures influence the functional properties of the kelp Ecklonia radiata. Comparing kelp growing on human-made pilings with kelp on nearby natural reefs, the researchers found that erosion rates were consistently lower on the artificial structures across the estuary. These findings indicate that urbanisation can affect coastal ecosystem functioning by altering key functional attributes of habitat-forming species such as kelp. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Artificial coastal structures always improve the overall health of kelp forests compared with natural reefs."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Researchers found that kelp grows faster on artificial structures than on natural reefs in urban estuaries."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Urbanisation can influence coastal ecosystem functioning by changing functional properties of kelp."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Studies of kelp erosion have typically ignored the effects of artificial structures in estuaries."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is correct because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that Mayer-Pinto and colleagues compared kelp growing on artificial pilings and natural reefs and found consistent differences in erosion rates. The text then draws a broader conclusion: that urbanisation can influence coastal ecosystem functioning by affecting the functional properties of habitat-forming species like kelp. Choice C captures both the specific findings and the broader implication emphasized in the passage. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not claim that artificial structures always improve kelp health overall. It discusses erosion rates only and does not generalize about overall health. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not mention growth rates. The study focuses on erosion as a functional property, not on how fast kelp grows. Choice D is incorrect because, although the text notes that impacts on functional attributes are often overlooked (as background context), the main focus is on what the researchers discovered, not on critiquing previous research trends.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Spanning more than six hundred pages, The Invention of Nature by historian Andrea Wulf presents an expansive account of the life and influence of Alexander von Humboldt, a nineteenth-century naturalist whose ideas shaped modern environmental science. Drawing on Humboldt’s extensive journals, letters, and published works, Wulf traces how his travels and interdisciplinary thinking transformed scientific approaches to nature. Although the book succeeds in demonstrating Humboldt’s lasting intellectual legacy, its admiration for its subject sometimes results in limited critical engagement with the shortcomings or controversies surrounding his work. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The Invention of Nature overlooks many of Alexander von Humboldt’s scientific contributions in favor of focusing on his personal life."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Andrea Wulf’s book argues that Alexander von Humboldt was the most influential scientist of the nineteenth century without presenting sufficient historical evidence."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The Invention of Nature offers a detailed and engaging portrait of Alexander von Humboldt, but its perspective has a notable limitation."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The length and academic tone of The Invention of Nature make it inaccessible to readers unfamiliar with the history of science."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that The Invention of Nature is a wide-ranging and well-researched account of Alexander von Humboldt’s life and influence, emphasizing the book’s success in conveying his importance to environmental science. At the same time, the text identifies a limitation in the book’s approach: its largely admiring tone reduces critical examination of Humboldt’s flaws or controversies. Thus, the main idea is that the book is a valuable and comprehensive work with an important shortcoming. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not suggest that the book overlooks Humboldt’s scientific contributions. In fact, it emphasizes that the book thoroughly documents his intellectual influence. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not criticize the book for lacking evidence. On the contrary, it notes that Wulf draws on journals, letters, and published works to support her account. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not discuss the book’s accessibility, tone, or suitability for general readers. The criticism focuses on perspective and balance, not difficulty or readability.', 'information-ideas', 'medium', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Economist Maria López has found a negative relationship between the extent to which cities rely on short-term tourism and their long-term economic resilience. At first glance, this finding may seem counterintuitive—tourism generates immediate revenue and employment—but López argues that economies heavily dependent on tourism are especially vulnerable to sudden disruptions, such as natural disasters or public health crises. These shocks can rapidly reduce visitor numbers, creating economic instability that discourages sustained investment in other sectors. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Although tourism often provides immediate economic benefits to cities, it rarely produces long-term employment opportunities."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Although cities may appear economically successful when tourism forms a large part of their economies, such reliance can undermine long-term economic stability."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Cities that experience natural disasters tend to lose tourism revenue more quickly than revenue from other industries."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Although tourism attracts outside investment in cities, that investment typically declines once visitor numbers stabilize."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that while tourism may seem economically beneficial in the short term, cities that rely heavily on it are more vulnerable to sudden disruptions that create instability and discourage sustained economic development. Thus, the central idea is that dependence on tourism can weaken long-term economic resilience despite its apparent advantages. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not claim that tourism rarely produces long-term employment. Instead, it focuses on economic vulnerability and instability, not employment duration. Choice C is incorrect because, although the text mentions natural disasters as one example of a disruption, it does not compare tourism revenue losses with losses from other industries. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss how investment changes once tourism stabilizes. Rather, it emphasizes that instability caused by tourism dependence discourages diversification and sustained investment.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Some historians have argued that the scientific revolution began primarily in seventeenth-century Europe because of the rapid growth of printing, universities, and formal scientific institutions during that period. These conditions may indeed have helped accelerate scientific exchange, but emphasizing institutional expansion over earlier developments risks overlooking substantial experimental and mathematical work produced in the medieval Islamic world. Treating European institutional growth as decisive therefore requires stronger justification than has so far been offered. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Although the scientific revolution is commonly associated with seventeenth-century Europe, scholars disagree about which institutions were most influential during that period."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Although European scientific institutions expanded rapidly in the seventeenth century, they were directly modeled on earlier institutions from the medieval Islamic world."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Although linking the scientific revolution primarily to seventeenth-century Europe is plausible, that view has not adequately accounted for earlier scientific contributions."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Although printing and universities expanded in seventeenth-century Europe, scientific progress during that period was slower than in earlier centuries."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage acknowledges that seventeenth-century Europe had conditions that may have fostered scientific progress, making the argument plausible. However, it criticizes scholars for prioritizing those conditions without sufficiently addressing evidence of significant earlier scientific work, particularly from the medieval Islamic world. Thus, the main idea is that while the later dating has merit, it fails to convincingly engage with competing evidence. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not focus on disagreements about which European institutions were most influential. Instead, it focuses on whether European institutional growth should be privileged over earlier scientific developments. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not claim that European institutions were modeled on earlier Islamic ones. It mentions earlier scientific contributions, not institutional imitation. Choice D is incorrect because the passage makes no claim about the relative speed of scientific progress across periods. The issue is not comparative pace but the interpretation of evidence used to explain origins.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'For much of the twentieth century, the hippocampus—a brain structure found in vertebrates—was primarily associated with the formation of long-term memory. This focus delayed broader consideration of the structure’s potential roles. Over the past several decades, however, neuroscience research has increasingly indicated that the hippocampus also contributes to spatial navigation and emotional regulation, and recent studies by neuroscientist May-Britt Moser and colleagues have identified neural mechanisms linking the hippocampus to systems involved in mapping physical environments. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The discovery of neural mechanisms involved in spatial mapping confirms that the hippocampus is exclusively responsible for memory formation."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Recent research has overturned earlier theories by showing that the hippocampus does not play a role in long-term memory."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The hippocampus was long understood mainly as a memory-related structure, but recent research has revealed additional functions."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Advances in neuroscience have demonstrated that spatial navigation relies more heavily on the hippocampus than on any other brain structure."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately captures the central idea of the passage. The text explains that the hippocampus was traditionally associated primarily with memory, but more recent research has expanded this view by identifying its involvement in spatial navigation and emotional regulation. The mention of specific studies serves to support this broader understanding. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not claim that the hippocampus is exclusively responsible for memory formation. In fact, the passage emphasizes that its functions extend beyond memory. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not suggest that earlier theories about memory were overturned or proven false; rather, it indicates that those theories were incomplete. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not compare the hippocampus’s importance to that of other brain structures or claim that it is the most important for spatial navigation.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'For decades, employers and psychologists have suggested that handwriting reveals stable personality traits—for example, that large handwriting signals confidence or that slanted letters indicate emotional expressiveness. However, a comprehensive review of graphology research by Geoffrey Dean and colleagues, drawing on multiple controlled studies comparing handwriting samples with independently assessed personality measures, found that while handwriting features are consistent for an individual, they show little reliable correlation with personality traits. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Personality psychologists have relied too heavily on handwriting analysis despite limited methodological rigor."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Research challenges the belief that handwriting provides dependable insight into a person’s personality."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Handwriting remains a useful tool for identifying individual differences, even if it cannot predict behavior."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Controlled studies of graphology are difficult to conduct because handwriting styles vary across contexts."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that many people believe handwriting reflects personality traits, but research reviewed by Dean and colleagues found little reliable correlation between handwriting features and independently measured personality traits. Thus, the central point is that empirical research does not support a commonly held belief about handwriting and personality. Choice A is incorrect because although the passage discusses research that evaluates handwriting analysis, it does not argue that psychologists have relied too heavily on it or criticize the field’s methodology as a whole. The focus is on the findings, not professional practice. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not claim that handwriting is useful for identifying individual differences beyond noting that handwriting features are consistent for an individual. The text does not suggest this consistency makes handwriting a useful analytical tool. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not discuss difficulties in conducting handwriting studies or variability across contexts. Instead, it reports the results of multiple controlled studies that have already been conducted.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the early twentieth century, linguist Franz Boas argued that the grammatical categories of a language shape how its speakers habitually attend to experience, an idea that later scholars would associate with linguistic relativity. Boas’s position, however, might have remained marginal were it not for his student Edward Sapir, who expanded Boas’s observations into a more systematic framework and promoted them through widely read lectures and publications. Sapir’s refinements and dissemination of the idea positioned him as a central figure in its development, even though the foundational insight originated with Boas. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Edward Sapir played a crucial role in shaping and spreading an idea about language that originated with Franz Boas."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Franz Boas’s ideas about language and cognition were rejected by most linguists until the late twentieth century."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The theory of linguistic relativity originated entirely with Edward Sapir rather than with earlier linguists."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Linguistic relativity demonstrates that speakers of different languages are unable to perceive the world in similar ways."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it most accurately captures the passage’s central idea. The text explains that although Boas first proposed the idea linking language and habitual thought, Sapir expanded, systematized, and widely disseminated it. The passage emphasizes Sapir’s crucial role in refining and promoting an existing idea rather than originating it. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not discuss widespread rejection of Boas’s ideas or provide information about how other linguists responded to them over time. Choice C is incorrect because it contradicts the passage, which clearly states that the foundational insight originated with Boas, not Sapir, even though Sapir later developed it further. Choice D is incorrect because it overstates the implications of linguistic relativity. The passage discusses how language may shape habitual attention, not that speakers of different languages are incapable of perceiving the world similarly.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Conservation efforts increasingly recognize that restoring ecological function on privately owned land can play a significant role in addressing habitat loss. Through the Partners for Fish and Wildlife Program, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service collaborates with private landowners to restore wetlands, forests, riparian zones, and upland habitats. In Vermont, biologists based at the Lake Champlain Fish and Wildlife Conservation Office in Essex Junction work with landowners to remove barriers to fish passage, restore native vegetation, and implement projects such as wetland rehabilitation and culvert replacement. By combining technical expertise with voluntary, long-term stewardship from landowners, the program supports migratory birds, pollinators, fish, and federally listed species. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The Partners for Fish and Wildlife Program depends primarily on federal ownership of land to succeed."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Cooperative, habitat-based restoration on private land can effectively support wildlife conservation."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Restoration projects in Vermont focus more on fish passage than on other conservation priorities."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Technical assistance provided by conservation biologists is the most important factor in ecosystem recovery."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately captures the central idea of the passage: that collaborative, habitat-focused restoration efforts on private lands can effectively contribute to conservation goals. The passage first establishes the broader idea that private lands are important for conservation and then illustrates this point through the Partners for Fish and Wildlife Program in Vermont. Choice A is incorrect because the passage emphasizes work on private land rather than federal ownership, directly contradicting the claim made in this option. Choice C is incorrect because it focuses too narrowly on one type of restoration activity. Fish passage is mentioned as an example, but the passage clearly describes a wide range of restoration efforts. Choice D is incorrect because, although technical assistance is discussed, the passage does not argue that it is the single most important factor in ecosystem recovery; instead, it highlights collaboration and habitat-based approaches more broadly.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Astronomer Clyde Tombaugh is best known for his association with three major observational projects early in his career. While working at Lowell Observatory in 1930, Tombaugh discovered Pluto using a blink comparator, a finding that relied heavily on a systematic photographic survey designed by the observatory’s director. Tombaugh later participated in surveys of near-Earth asteroids and variable stars, but these efforts involved collaborative data collection and yielded no comparable independent discoveries. Of the projects Tombaugh is associated with, the discovery of Pluto represents the one in which his individual observational work played the most central role. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Of the projects associated with Tombaugh, the discovery of Pluto most prominently reflects his individual contribution."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Tombaugh’s later astronomical surveys were more scientifically important than his discovery of Pluto."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The blink comparator was the primary reason Pluto was discovered at Lowell Observatory."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Collaborative research methods became increasingly common in astronomy during Tombaugh’s career."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately captures the passage’s central point: although Tombaugh was involved in multiple astronomical projects, the discovery of Pluto is the one most strongly attributable to his own independent observational work. The passage contrasts Pluto’s discovery with later projects that were collaborative and less individually distinctive. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not claim that Tombaugh’s later surveys were more important than the Pluto discovery; in fact, it implies the opposite by emphasizing the singular significance of Pluto. Choice C is incorrect because, while the blink comparator is mentioned as a tool, the passage does not argue that it—rather than Tombaugh’s work—was the primary reason for the discovery. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not make a general claim about historical trends in astronomy; collaboration is mentioned only to contextualize Tombaugh’s later work, not as a broader argument.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Nineteenth-century philosopher Karl Marx is frequently associated with the phrase “the dictatorship of the proletariat,” which is often taken to describe a detailed and enduring system of political governance in Marxist theory. Note the common assumption: as scholars such as Hal Draper have argued, Marx used the phrase sparingly and primarily to describe a transitional stage between capitalism and a classless communist society, not a fully specified or permanent political order. The term attracted relatively little sustained attention in Marx’s own lifetime and was later elevated by twentieth-century political leaders and theorists seeking textual justification for highly centralized state systems. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Although Marx is widely associated with the concept of the dictatorship of the proletariat, the concept was largely ignored until twentieth-century political leaders developed it into a detailed system of governance."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Some twentieth-century theorists expanded Marx’s concept of the dictatorship of the proletariat beyond its role in Marx’s work, but the concept nevertheless accurately represents Marx’s political philosophy."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Marx’s concept of the dictatorship of the proletariat has been interpreted as a permanent political system, though it was originally intended to describe a temporary stage in historical development."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The prominence of the dictatorship of the proletariat in Marxist discourse reflects later political reinterpretations rather than the centrality of the concept in Marx’s own writings."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the passage. The text emphasizes that although Marx is now strongly associated with the phrase “dictatorship of the proletariat,” his actual use of the term was limited and context-specific. The passage explains that the concept gained its later prominence largely because twentieth-century political actors and theorists elevated it to legitimize their own political systems, not because it occupied a central role in Marx’s original work. Choice A is incorrect because, while the passage notes that the concept gained prominence in the twentieth century, it does not claim that later figures merely developed Marx’s idea neutrally; rather, it suggests that they promoted it selectively for their own ends. The choice also fails to capture the passage’s emphasis on Marx’s limited use of the term. Choice B is incorrect because the passage does not endorse the view that later interpretations accurately represent Marx’s political philosophy. Instead, it implies that these interpretations depart significantly from Marx’s original, narrowly defined usage. Choice C is incorrect because, although it correctly notes that Marx conceived of the dictatorship of the proletariat as a transitional stage, this point is subordinate to the passage’s main argument: that the concept’s later reputation is disproportionate to its importance in Marx’s writings.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Economic historian Leah Platt Boustan has documented a negative relationship between rapid urban highway expansion in mid-twentieth-century United States cities and long-term population retention in those cities’ central districts. At first glance, this pattern seems unexpected, since new highways were intended to improve mobility and stimulate economic growth. However, Boustan explains that highway construction often accelerated suburbanization by making it easier for residents and businesses to relocate outside city centers, thereby weakening urban tax bases and reducing incentives for continued investment in downtown areas. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Although highway construction was designed to strengthen urban economies, it often had the unintended effect of encouraging population loss from city centers."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Because suburban areas offered more space and lower housing costs, most residents chose to leave urban centers once highways were built."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Highway expansion improved transportation efficiency but failed to generate sufficient economic growth to offset construction costs."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Urban population decline in the twentieth century was caused primarily by residents’ dissatisfaction with public transportation systems."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer because it accurately captures the central claim of the passage. The text explains that although urban highway expansion was expected to promote economic growth, research by Boustan shows that it instead contributed to population loss in city centers by facilitating suburbanization and discouraging sustained urban investment. Choice A reflects both the initial expectation and the counterintuitive outcome emphasized in the text. Choice B is incorrect because, while the passage mentions suburbanization, it does not attribute residents’ relocation decisions to housing costs or personal preferences for space. These details are not discussed in the text. Choice C is incorrect because the passage does not evaluate highway construction in terms of cost-effectiveness or economic return on investment. Its focus is on population patterns and urban decline, not fiscal efficiency. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not discuss public transportation dissatisfaction as a cause of urban population decline. The decline is linked specifically to highway expansion and its role in enabling suburban relocation.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In research on spatial navigation and brain plasticity, Eleanor Maguire and colleagues investigated whether intensive navigation demands could produce measurable neural changes in adults. The researchers focused on licensed London taxi drivers, who must memorize thousands of streets and landmarks to pass the Knowledge, a rigorous qualifying examination. Although acquiring this expertise requires years of effort and is often associated with stress and high attrition rates, the study found that experienced taxi drivers exhibited increased gray matter volume in the posterior hippocampus, suggesting that sustained navigational demands can induce adaptive structural changes in the brain. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Research shows that the stress associated with becoming a licensed London taxi driver often outweighs the cognitive benefits of navigation training."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Although adults are typically thought to have limited neural plasticity, research indicates that intensive navigation experience can lead to structural brain changes."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The hippocampus plays a central role in spatial memory, making it essential for professions that require navigation expertise."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Studies of London taxi drivers reveal that most adults are incapable of mastering complex spatial environments."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately captures the passage’s central claim: that sustained, demanding navigation experience in adulthood can lead to measurable structural changes in the brain. The text emphasizes that despite the difficulty and stress associated with acquiring navigational expertise, Maguire and colleagues found evidence of adaptive neural changes, specifically increased gray matter volume in the posterior hippocampus. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not compare stress costs with cognitive benefits or suggest that stress outweighs the benefits. While stress and attrition are mentioned, they serve as background context rather than the main point. Choice C is incorrect because, although the hippocampus’s role in spatial memory is implied, the passage does not aim to explain the general function of the hippocampus. Instead, it focuses on evidence of experience-dependent brain plasticity. Choice D is incorrect because it directly contradicts the passage. The study demonstrates that some adults are capable of mastering complex spatial environments and that doing so is associated with neural adaptation, not incapacity.', 'information-ideas', 'hard', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the mid-twentieth century, the development of commercial jet aircraft, such as the Boeing 707, transformed long-distance travel by dramatically reducing flight times between continents. This technological shift made international travel more accessible to a broader segment of the population and enabled businesses to operate across national borders more efficiently. As air travel became faster and more reliable, tourism expanded rapidly, and cultural exchange between distant regions increased. These changes reshaped economic activity and personal mobility on a global scale. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The introduction of commercial jet aircraft created new possibilities for global travel and economic interaction."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The Boeing 707 was the most technologically advanced aircraft of the mid-twentieth century."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Tourism became the primary motivation for developing faster commercial airplanes."},{"id":"D","text":"D. International business depended entirely on air travel by the mid-twentieth century."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is correct because it best captures the passage’s central idea: that the development of commercial jet aircraft fundamentally expanded opportunities for international travel, business, tourism, and cultural exchange. The text emphasizes the broad effects of faster, more accessible air travel rather than focusing on a single outcome. Choice B is incorrect because although the Boeing 707 is mentioned as an example, the passage does not evaluate aircraft technology in comparative terms or argue that this plane was the most advanced of its era. The mention serves as context, not the main point. Choice C is incorrect because tourism is described as one result of faster air travel, not as the driving force behind the development of jet aircraft. The passage presents tourism as part of a broader set of consequences. Choice D is incorrect because the text does not claim that international business relied entirely on air travel. It states that air travel made cross-border business more efficient, not that it was the sole means of conducting it.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'To investigate how Neolithic people illuminated their homes, archaeologists led by Dr. Mark Williams reconstructed clay oil lamps based on fragments found in Neolithic sites in the British Isles. They filled these replica lamps with animal fat (tallow) and plant oil and then measured how much light each produced, how long it burned, and how smoke-filled the space became. The team discovered that tallow lamps burnt more brightly and for longer durations, but plant-oil lamps produced much less smoke, making them more comfortable for everyday use. Based on these experiments, the researchers concluded that Neolithic communities likely used different kinds of lamps depending on whether they needed sustained light or a cleaner-burning source indoors. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"Dr. Williams and his team proved that tallow lamps were universally preferred by Neolithic people."},{"id":"B","text":"Dr. Williams’s experiments show that Neolithic people likely used different types of lamps for different lighting needs."},{"id":"C","text":"Dr. Williams argues that Neolithic homes would have been filled with smoke from tallow lamps."},{"id":"D","text":"Dr. Williams’s research shows that plant-oil lamps were inadequate for ancient people’s lighting needs."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because the passage describes how the archaeologists tested two different lamp types and found that each had trade-offs: tallow gave more light and lasted longer, while plant oil burned cleaner. From these results, the researchers “concluded that Neolithic communities likely used different kinds of lamps depending on whether they needed sustained light or a cleaner-burning source indoors.” That clearly reflects the main idea: they used different lamps for different purposes. Choice A is incorrect because the text does not say tallow lamps were universally preferred—it says each lamp had its use. Choice C is incorrect because, although the passage mentions smoke, it’s not the main point; the focus is on which lamp was used when. Choice D is incorrect because the researchers did not say plant-oil lamps were inadequate—they actually highlight the advantage: less smoke.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1961, Jane Jacobs, an urban activist and writer, published The Death and Life of Great American Cities, a book that challenged prevailing ideas in city planning. At a time when many planners favored large-scale urban renewal projects, Jacobs argued that lively neighborhoods depend on mixed land use, walkable streets, and strong local communities. Her ideas influenced city officials, architects, and activists, encouraging a shift toward planning approaches that prioritized human-scale urban environments. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Urban renewal projects were widely supported by planners in the mid-twentieth century."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Jane Jacobs opposed most forms of city planning in the United States."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Jane Jacobs’s work played an important role in reshaping how cities were planned."},{"id":"D","text":"D. City officials ignored Jane Jacobs’s ideas about walkable neighborhoods."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately states the main idea of the text. The passage explains that Jane Jacobs published a book that challenged dominant city-planning ideas and that her arguments went on to influence planners, officials, and activists. Taken together, these points show that Jacobs’s work helped reshape approaches to urban planning. Choice A is incorrect. Although the passage mentions that large-scale urban renewal was popular at the time, this information serves as background context rather than the central focus of the text. Choice B is incorrect. The passage does not claim that Jacobs opposed all city planning; instead, it explains that she challenged certain prevailing approaches and promoted alternative principles. Choice D is incorrect. The passage explicitly states that Jacobs’s ideas influenced officials and planners, directly contradicting the claim that her ideas were ignored.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1906, chemist Leo Baekeland introduced Bakelite, the first fully synthetic plastic. Unlike earlier materials, Bakelite could be molded when heated and then permanently hardened, making it especially useful for mass production. Manufacturers quickly adopted it to create affordable consumer goods such as radio casings, electrical insulators, and kitchenware. As a result, products that had previously been expensive or fragile became widely accessible to the public. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Bakelite was mainly used to manufacture radios and household items in the early twentieth century."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Baekeland’s invention of Bakelite made it possible to mass-produce durable goods that became widely available."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Early plastics were more fragile and expensive than materials used in later consumer products."},{"id":"D","text":"D.The chemical properties of Bakelite allowed it to harden permanently after being heated."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it most accurately captures the main idea of the passage. The text introduces Baekeland’s invention of Bakelite and explains that its moldable yet durable nature allowed manufacturers to mass-produce affordable goods, making many products widely accessible for the first time. The passage focuses on both the innovation and its broader impact. Choice A is incorrect because it focuses on specific examples of Bakelite’s use, which are details that support the main idea but do not fully capture it. Choice C is incorrect because, although the passage contrasts Bakelite with earlier materials, this comparison serves as background information rather than the central point of the text. Choice D is incorrect because it highlights a single technical characteristic of Bakelite. While accurate, this detail does not address the broader significance of the invention emphasized in the passage.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In the early twentieth century, public libraries expanded rapidly across the United States, aided in part by funding from philanthropist Andrew Carnegie. These libraries offered free access to books, newspapers, and educational resources at a time when such materials were often unaffordable for many people. As a result, individuals could pursue self-education, improve literacy skills, and engage more actively in civic life. Libraries also became important community spaces, hosting lectures, reading groups, and other public events. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The expansion of public libraries in the early twentieth century created new educational and social opportunities for many people."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Andrew Carnegie personally managed the daily operations of most public libraries in the United States."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Public libraries in the early twentieth century focused primarily on hosting lectures and community events."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Books and newspapers were generally too expensive for most people to purchase in the early twentieth century."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'Choice A is the best answer. The passage explains that the expansion of public libraries allowed people to access reading materials, pursue self-education, improve literacy, and participate in community activities. All of these represent new opportunities made possible by the growth of public libraries. Choice B is incorrect. The passage mentions Carnegie’s financial support, but it does not say that he managed libraries’ daily operations. This choice overstates a minor detail. Choice C is incorrect. Hosting lectures and events is mentioned, but it is only one example of how libraries served communities, not the central focus of the passage. A main idea must encompass more of the text. Choice D is incorrect. While the passage notes that books and newspapers were often unaffordable, this point serves as background information explaining why libraries mattered, not the passage’s main idea.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Musk oxen display a collective defense behavior when threatened by predators such as wolves. When a predator approaches, adult musk oxen form a tight outward-facing circle, positioning calves in the center. This formation allows the adults to use their horns to deter attacks while shielding vulnerable members of the group. Researchers note that this defensive circle is consistently observed in response to wolf packs but not during encounters with less dangerous animals, suggesting that the behavior is triggered by specific predatory threats. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Researchers have not identified how musk oxen protect their calves from predators."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Musk oxen use a coordinated group formation as a defense specifically against serious predators."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Wolves rely on pack hunting to prey on large herbivores such as musk oxen."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Many herd animals place their young in the center of the group during migration."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer. The passage explains that musk oxen form a coordinated defensive circle when faced with dangerous predators like wolves and emphasizes that this behavior is not observed in less threatening situations. This supports the idea that the behavior is a specific, collective defense response. Choice A is incorrect. The passage clearly describes how musk oxen protect their calves; it does not suggest uncertainty about their defensive strategies. Choice C is incorrect. While wolves are mentioned, the passage focuses on musk oxen’s behavior, not on wolf hunting strategies. This choice shifts the focus away from the main subject. Choice D is incorrect. Although the passage mentions protecting calves, it does not discuss migration or claim that this behavior is common across many herd animals.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'In 1935, the Federal Writers’ Project (FWP) was established as part of President Franklin D. Roosevelt’s New Deal and operated under the Works Progress Administration (WPA). The project was designed to provide employment for unemployed writers, editors, researchers, and other white-collar workers during the Great Depression. As part of a group of initiatives known collectively as Federal Project Number One, the FWP employed thousands of individuals at its peak. Through this work, participants produced state and city guides, oral histories, ethnographies, and other publications intended to create a detailed record of American life. Many of these publications, including the American Guide Series, made cultural and historical information accessible to a broad public. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Jobs provided by the FWP were limited primarily to writers rather than other professionals."},{"id":"B","text":"B. President Roosevelt created Federal Project Number One to promote tourism during the Great Depression."},{"id":"C","text":"C. During the Great Depression, many Americans lacked access to reliable information about their communities."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The Federal Writers’ Project successfully provided employment while producing influential documentation of American life."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'Choice D is the best answer because it most accurately captures the passage’s central focus. The text explains that the Federal Writers’ Project was created to employ unemployed white-collar workers and that, through this employment, the project produced guides, histories, and other publications documenting American life. The passage emphasizes both the job-creation function of the FWP and the lasting significance of its cultural output. Choice A is incorrect. While the text notes that writers were among those employed, it also explicitly mentions editors, researchers, and other white-collar workers. More importantly, the passage’s main idea is not about restricting jobs to one group but about the broader success and purpose of the project. Choice B is incorrect. The text mentions Federal Project Number One and the production of travel guides, but it does not state or imply that promoting tourism was the primary goal of the initiative. This choice misrepresents supporting details as the main idea. Choice C is incorrect. Although the passage suggests that the FWP made information more accessible, it does not focus on Americans’ lack of access as its central point. Instead, this idea serves as background context for understanding why the project’s work mattered.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'A white oak known as the Tree That Owns Itself stands at the corner of Dearing and Finley Streets in Athens, Georgia, and is associated with a long-standing local legend claiming that it legally owns itself and the land immediately surrounding its trunk. According to the story, Colonel William Henry Jackson, a professor at the University of Georgia, deeded the tree ownership of itself around 1832 out of personal affection. Although a newspaper article from 1890 described such a deed, no legal record of it has ever been found, and under common law a tree cannot hold property. Nevertheless, Athens–Clarke County maintains the tree as a public street tree, and a replacement sapling—grown from an acorn of the original—continues the tradition as a valued cultural landmark. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Colonel William Henry Jackson successfully transferred legal ownership of land to a tree in nineteenth-century Georgia."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The Tree That Owns Itself is a legally recognized property holder under modern municipal law."},{"id":"C","text":"C. A popular legend about a self-owning tree persists despite the lack of legal evidence supporting it."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Athens–Clarke County planted a replacement tree primarily to preserve rare specimens of Quercus alba."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it accurately reflects the passage’s central point: the enduring story that the tree owns itself continues to be embraced culturally even though there is no legal documentation and property law does not support such ownership. The text presents the legend, explains why it lacks legal validity, and notes that the tree is still symbolically protected and maintained. Choice A is incorrect because it goes beyond the information in the passage. The text explicitly states that no deed has ever been found and that a tree cannot legally own property, so Jackson did not successfully transfer ownership. Choice B is incorrect because it directly contradicts the passage. While the tree is maintained by municipal authorities, the text makes clear that it does not have legal personhood or recognized ownership rights. Choice D is incorrect because it misrepresents a detail as the main idea. Although a replacement sapling was planted, the passage emphasizes the continuation of the legend and cultural significance, not botanical conservation as the primary purpose.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'The following text is adapted from Anne of Green Gables by L. M. Montgomery. “Kindred spirits are not so scarce as I used to think. It’s splendid to find out there are so many of them in the world.” Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. The speaker believes that true friendship is rare and difficult to maintain."},{"id":"B","text":"B. The speaker feels disappointed that she once misunderstood other people."},{"id":"C","text":"C. The speaker expresses happiness at realizing she is not as alone in her way of thinking as she once believed."},{"id":"D","text":"D. The speaker argues that people in the world are more similar than they appear."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it most accurately captures the central idea of the excerpt. The speaker reflects on a change in perspective: she once believed that “kindred spirits” were rare but now finds joy in realizing that many people share her feelings and outlook. The emphasis is on emotional satisfaction and connection, not on argument or general social commentary. Choice A is incorrect because the excerpt directly contradicts the idea that true companionship is rare; the speaker explicitly states that kindred spirits are not scarce. Choice B is incorrect because while the speaker acknowledges a past misconception, the tone of the excerpt is positive and celebratory, not disappointed or regretful. Choice D is incorrect because it overgeneralizes the speaker’s personal realization into a broad claim about humanity. The text focuses on the speaker’s emotional response, not on making a general argument about human similarity.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Müllerian mimicry is an evolutionary phenomenon observed in certain toxic or unpalatable species, particularly insects such as butterflies. In this form of mimicry, multiple species share similar warning colors or patterns, which signal danger to predators. Because all participating species are genuinely harmful, predators that learn to avoid one species are more likely to avoid others with the same appearance. Biologists suggest that Müllerian mimicry evolves because it reduces the number of fatal encounters each species experiences while predators learn to recognize the warning signal. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Biologists are uncertain how predators learn to avoid toxic insects with warning coloration."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Müllerian mimicry allows toxic species to benefit by sharing a common warning signal to predators."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Most butterflies rely on visual signals rather than chemical defenses to survive predation."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Müllerian mimicry occurs when harmless species imitate the appearance of toxic species."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Choice B is the best answer because it accurately captures the central idea of the passage. The text explains that Müllerian mimicry involves multiple genuinely harmful species sharing similar warning coloration and that this shared signal benefits all of them by reducing predation as predators learn to avoid the pattern. Choice A is incorrect because the passage does not express uncertainty about how predators learn to avoid toxic species. Instead, it explains that predators do learn to associate the shared warning signal with danger. Choice C is incorrect because although butterflies are mentioned, the passage does not compare visual signals with chemical defenses or claim that visual signals are more important. Choice D is incorrect because it confuses Müllerian mimicry with Batesian mimicry. The passage explicitly states that Müllerian mimicry involves species that are all genuinely harmful, not harmless imitators.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0),
  ('mcq', 'rw', 'Urban heat islands occur when cities experience higher temperatures than surrounding rural areas, largely due to heat-absorbing surfaces such as asphalt and concrete. Climate scientist Brian Stone Jr. and his colleagues have studied how urban tree cover affects this phenomenon. Their research indicates that neighborhoods with dense tree canopies can experience daytime temperatures several degrees lower than nearby areas with sparse vegetation, suggesting that urban trees play a significant role in moderating local heat. Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', '[{"id":"A","text":"A. Climate scientists are primarily focused on understanding how asphalt contributes to rising urban temperatures."},{"id":"B","text":"B. Urban heat islands occur because cities contain fewer plants than rural areas."},{"id":"C","text":"C. Trees in cities can significantly reduce local temperatures and lessen the effects of urban heat islands."},{"id":"D","text":"D. Urban neighborhoods vary widely in temperature depending on their geographic location."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Choice C is the best answer because it accurately captures the central finding described in the passage: research shows that urban tree cover can lower temperatures and reduce the effects of urban heat islands. Choice A is incorrect because, although heat-absorbing surfaces are mentioned, the focus of the research is on the cooling role of trees, not asphalt itself. Choice B is incorrect because it oversimplifies the passage. While vegetation is relevant, the text emphasizes research findings about tree canopy reducing temperatures, not merely the absence of plants. Choice D is incorrect because the passage does not discuss geographic location as the primary cause of temperature differences; instead, it highlights the role of urban tree cover.', 'information-ideas', 'easy', 0, 0);
